{"title_page": "Coronavirus recession", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Global Recession|2=Talk:Coronavirus recession#Requested move 3 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|2020 economic downturn}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Merge to|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|discuss=Talk:Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Proposed merge of Coronavirus recession into Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{globalize|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:DowJones2020crash.png|thumb|Movement of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] between December 2019 and March 2020, showing the all-time high in February, and the crash in February and March during the COVID-19 pandemic]]\n\nThe '''Coronavirus recession''' , also known as '''Corona Recession''' is an [[economic recession]] which started affecting the [[world economy]] in [[2020]] due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/3/21/21188541/coronavirus-news-recession-economy-unemployment-stock-market-jobs-gdp|title=The coronavirus recession is already here|last=Stewart|first=Emily|date=21 March 2020|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Islam|first=Faisal|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51984470|title=Coronavirus recession not yet a depression|date=20 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6695294/the-coronavirus-recession-has-arrived/|title=The coronavirus recession has arrived|last=Times|first=The Canberra|date=25 March 2020|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> It is one [[socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. While economic data takes time to be collected, many economists agree that the recession is already happening.<ref name=\":0\" /> This has also been supported by findings from [[Purchasing Managers' Index|surveys of purchasing managers]] in the [[United States]], [[Europe]] and [[China]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tokyo|first=Harriet Torry in Washington, Paul Hannon in London and Megumi Fujikawa in|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-could-trigger-global-recession-says-imf-11585046688|title=Coronavirus Triggers Record Drops in U.S., European Business Activity|date=24 March 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/economy/china-services-employment-coronavirus/index.html|title=China's economy could shrink for the first time in decades because of the coronavirus|last=Business|first=Laura He, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The United States currently has almost five times as many unemployment claims as during the previous peak in 1982.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21|title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=2020-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n[[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] managing director [[Kristalina Georgieva]] on March 24 declared in a statement that the [[global economy]] will contract in 2020 and this \"recession [is] at least as bad as during the global financial crisis or worse.\" Almost 80 countries have asked the IMF for help.<ref>[https://www.afr.com/policy/economy/imf-forecasts-2020-global-recession-recovery-in-2021-20200324-p54d7h IMF forecasts 2020 global recession, recovery in 2021]</ref>{{subscription required}}\n\nMany countries with large economies, such as Italy and Spain, have enacted [[quarantine]] policies. This has led to the disruption of business activities in many economic sectors.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Developing countries are also forecast to be severely impacted by the coronavirus.<ref>[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3563616 Forecasting the Economic Impact of Coronavirus on Developing Countries.] ''Political Economy - Development: Health eJournal.'' Social Science Research Network. Accessed 30 March 2020.</ref>\n\n== Financial crisis ==\n{{Main article|2020 stock market crash}}\n{{see also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe global [[2020 stock market crash|stock market crash]] began on the 20 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Samuelson |first=Robert J. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/what-crash-2020-means/ |title=What Crash of 2020 Means |date=12 March 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wearden (earlier) |first=Graeme |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live |title=Wall Street and FTSE 100 plunge on worst day since 1987 \u2013 as it happened |date=12 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=12 March 2020 |last2=Jolly |first2=Jasper |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/10/stock-market-crash-2020-everything-you-need-to-kno.aspx |title=Stock Market Crash 2020: Everything You Need to Know |last=Williams |first=Sean |date=10 March 2020 |website=The Motley Fool |language=en |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Global markets into early March became extremely volatile, with large swings occurring in global markets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1748051/dow-industrials-surge-500-points-extending-volatile-streak/? |title=Asian shares rise following stimulus-led surge on Wall St |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |website=MyNorthwest}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-volatile-is-the-coronavirus-stricken-stock-market-after-the-worst-week-since-2008-the-dow-is-now-on-pace-for-its-best-week-since-2011-2020-03-04 |title=Wild stock-market swings are 'emotionally and intellectually wearing' on Wall Street |last=DeCambre |first=Mark |date=7 March 2020 |website=MarketWatch |language=en-US |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 9&nbsp;March, most global markets reported severe contractions, mainly in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and a described [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first1=Laura|last1=He|first2=Clare|last2=Duffy|first3=Julia|last3=Horowitz|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/08/investing/stock-dow-futures-coronavirus/index.html |title=US stocks halted after falling 7%. Global stocks plunge as oil crashes and coronavirus fear spreads |access-date=15 March 2020 |website=CNN}}</ref> This became colloquially known as Black Monday I, and at the time was the worst drop since the [[Great Recession]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/stock-markets-ftse-100-oil-prices-coronavirus-black-monday-a4382156.html |title=Black Monday: Fourth biggest City fall as virus panic hits markets |last=Prynn |first=Jonathon |last2=English |first2=Simon |date=9 March 2020 |website=Evening Standard |language=en |access-date=13 March 2020 |last3=Murphy |first3=Joe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Recession by sector ==\n\n=== Retail sector ===\nShopping centers around the world responded by reducing hours or closing down temporarily in response. As of 18 March 2020, the footfall to shopping centers fell by up-to 30%, with significant impact in every continent.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.aislelabs.com/blog/2020/03/23/how-shopping-centres-responding-coronavirus/  |title=How Shopping Centres Globally are Responding to Coronavirus by Aislelabs|author=Inc, Aislelabs|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> [[Simon Property Group]] became the first major US-based mall operator to close all centers on the 18th March, with government mandated closures in UAE, Italy, Germany, Spain, Brazil and Austria as of 23 March.\n\n===Transportation sector===\n{{generalize|section|date=March 2020}}\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation}}\n[[File:A nearly empty flight from PEK to LAX amid the COVID-19 pandemic 1.jpg|thumb|A nearly empty flight from [[Beijing]] to [[Los Angeles]] during the pandemic]]\n\nThe pandemic has had a significant impact on aviation industry due to [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the resulting travel restrictions]] as well as slump in demand among travelers. Significant reductions in passenger numbers has resulted in planes flying empty between airports and the cancellation of flights.\n\n=== Restaurant sector ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\nThe 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic has impacted the restaurant business. In the beginning of March 2020, some major cities in the US announced that bars and restaurants would be closed to sit-down diners and limited to [[Food delivery|takeout orders and delivery]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319091659/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some employees were fired, and more employees lacked [[sick leave]] in the sector compared to similar sectors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus exposes sick leave gap for retail, restaurant workers |url=https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/ |website=Press Enterprise |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318153437/https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nber.org/papers/w26832.pdf Sick leave] ''[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]''</ref>\n\n== Recession by country ==\n=== Australia ===\nUp to a million people have been laid off due to effects of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henriques-Gomes|first=Luke|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/24/newly-unemployed-australians-queue-at-centrelink-offices-as-mygov-website-crashes-again|title=Newly unemployed Australians queue at Centrelink offices as MyGov website crashes again|date=24 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Over 280,000 individuals applied for unemployment support at the peak day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/surge-in-demand-280-000-ask-centrelink-for-help-in-one-day-20200325-p54dwn.html|title='Surge in demand': 280,000 ask Centrelink for help in one day|last=Bonyhady|first=Nick|date=2020-03-25|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHousing prices in Australia could drop up to 20% as a result of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farrer|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/20/australian-housing-market-will-hit-the-wall-in-coronavirus-recession-experts-say|title=Australian housing market will hit the wall in coronavirus recession, experts say|date=19 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\n\nMinister of Finance of [[Hesse]] [[Thomas Sch\u00e4fer]] was found dead on 28 March 2020. Sch\u00e4fer left a suicide note, where he mentions the \"hopeless\" economic situation in the country as one of the reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tichyseinblick.de/daili-es-sentials/zum-tod-des-hessischen-finanzministers-thomas-schaefer/|title=Zum Tod des hessischen Finanzministers Thomas Sch\u00e4fer|date=2020-03-29|website=Tichys Einblick|language=de}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\nA new record of unemployment claims was made, with 3.3 million claims made in the week ending on 21 March, with the previous record being 700,000 from 1982.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21 |title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew |date=2020-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Restaurant patronage has fallen sharply across the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business|last=Molla|first=Rani |date=16 March 2020|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> and major airlines are reducing their operations on a large scale.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/airline-news/2020/03/18/coronavirus-travel-fallout-united-jetblue-allegiant-slash-flights/2863432001/ |title=American Airlines cuts 55,000 flights, parks 450 planes amid coronavirus: 'Fight of our lives'|last=Gilbertson|first=Dawn |website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three car manufacturers]] have all halted production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/business/gm-ford-automakers-us-shut-down/index.html |title=GM, Ford and other automakers to halt production in the US|last=Business|first=Peter Valdes-Dapena and Vanessa Yurkevich, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[yield curve#Inverted yield curve|yield curve inverted]] in  2019, usually indicative of a forthcoming recession.<ref>{{cite web |title=A closely followed recession indicator is flashing its most worrying sign in 12 years {{!}} Markets Insider |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644 |website=markets.businessinsider.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190930224654/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644 |archivedate=September 30, 2019 |date=May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-09/u-s-yield-curve-inverts-for-the-first-time-since-march |title=U.S. Yield Curve Inverts for the First Time Since March |website=www.bloomberg.com |date=May 2019}}</ref> The [[St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index]] increased sharply from below zero<!--Feb 21--> to 5.8<!--March 20--> during March 2020.<ref name=STLFSI2blog>{{cite web |title=The St. Louis Fed's Financial Stress Index, Version 2.0 {{!}} FRED Blog |url=https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327224916/https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/ |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live |quote=The revised STLFSI, however, has increased sharply\u2014reminiscent of the worst of the financial market turmoil during the Great Recession in 2008-2009\u2014registering a value close to 5.8.}}</ref><ref name=STLFSI2>{{cite web |title=St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index (STLFSI2) |url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2 |website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222839/https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2 |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019-nCoV}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in economics]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Global Recession|2=Talk:Coronavirus recession#Requested move 3 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|2020 economic downturn}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Merge to|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|discuss=Talk:Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Proposed merge of Coronavirus recession into Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{globalize|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:DowJones2020crash.png|thumb|Movement of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] between December 2019 and March 2020, showing the all-time high in February, and the crash in February and March during the COVID-19 pandemic]]\n\nThe '''Coronavirus recession''' is an [[economic recession]] which started affecting the [[world economy]] in [[2020]] due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/3/21/21188541/coronavirus-news-recession-economy-unemployment-stock-market-jobs-gdp|title=The coronavirus recession is already here|last=Stewart|first=Emily|date=21 March 2020|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Islam|first=Faisal|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-51984470|title=Coronavirus recession not yet a depression|date=20 March 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6695294/the-coronavirus-recession-has-arrived/|title=The coronavirus recession has arrived|last=Times|first=The Canberra|date=25 March 2020|website=The Canberra Times|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> It is one [[socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. While economic data takes time to be collected, many economists agree that the recession is already happening.<ref name=\":0\" /> This has also been supported by findings from [[Purchasing Managers' Index|surveys of purchasing managers]] in the [[United States]], [[Europe]] and [[China]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tokyo|first=Harriet Torry in Washington, Paul Hannon in London and Megumi Fujikawa in|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-could-trigger-global-recession-says-imf-11585046688|title=Coronavirus Triggers Record Drops in U.S., European Business Activity|date=24 March 2020|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/04/economy/china-services-employment-coronavirus/index.html|title=China's economy could shrink for the first time in decades because of the coronavirus|last=Business|first=Laura He, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The United States currently has almost five times as many unemployment claims as during the previous peak in 1982.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21|title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=2020-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n[[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] managing director [[Kristalina Georgieva]] on March 24 declared in a statement that the [[global economy]] will contract in 2020 and this \"recession [is] at least as bad as during the global financial crisis or worse.\" Almost 80 countries have asked the IMF for help.<ref>[https://www.afr.com/policy/economy/imf-forecasts-2020-global-recession-recovery-in-2021-20200324-p54d7h IMF forecasts 2020 global recession, recovery in 2021]</ref>{{subscription required}}\n\nMany countries with large economies, such as Italy and Spain, have enacted [[quarantine]] policies. This has led to the disruption of business activities in many economic sectors.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Developing countries are also forecast to be severely impacted by the coronavirus.<ref>[https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3563616 Forecasting the Economic Impact of Coronavirus on Developing Countries.] ''Political Economy - Development: Health eJournal.'' Social Science Research Network. Accessed 30 March 2020.</ref>\n\n== Financial crisis ==\n{{Main article|2020 stock market crash}}\n{{see also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe global [[2020 stock market crash|stock market crash]] began on the 20 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Samuelson |first=Robert J. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/what-crash-2020-means/ |title=What Crash of 2020 Means |date=12 March 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wearden (earlier) |first=Graeme |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live |title=Wall Street and FTSE 100 plunge on worst day since 1987 \u2013 as it happened |date=12 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=12 March 2020 |last2=Jolly |first2=Jasper |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/10/stock-market-crash-2020-everything-you-need-to-kno.aspx |title=Stock Market Crash 2020: Everything You Need to Know |last=Williams |first=Sean |date=10 March 2020 |website=The Motley Fool |language=en |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Global markets into early March became extremely volatile, with large swings occurring in global markets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1748051/dow-industrials-surge-500-points-extending-volatile-streak/? |title=Asian shares rise following stimulus-led surge on Wall St |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |website=MyNorthwest}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-volatile-is-the-coronavirus-stricken-stock-market-after-the-worst-week-since-2008-the-dow-is-now-on-pace-for-its-best-week-since-2011-2020-03-04 |title=Wild stock-market swings are 'emotionally and intellectually wearing' on Wall Street |last=DeCambre |first=Mark |date=7 March 2020 |website=MarketWatch |language=en-US |access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 9&nbsp;March, most global markets reported severe contractions, mainly in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and a described [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first1=Laura|last1=He|first2=Clare|last2=Duffy|first3=Julia|last3=Horowitz|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/08/investing/stock-dow-futures-coronavirus/index.html |title=US stocks halted after falling 7%. Global stocks plunge as oil crashes and coronavirus fear spreads |access-date=15 March 2020 |website=CNN}}</ref> This became colloquially known as Black Monday I, and at the time was the worst drop since the [[Great Recession]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/stock-markets-ftse-100-oil-prices-coronavirus-black-monday-a4382156.html |title=Black Monday: Fourth biggest City fall as virus panic hits markets |last=Prynn |first=Jonathon |last2=English |first2=Simon |date=9 March 2020 |website=Evening Standard |language=en |access-date=13 March 2020 |last3=Murphy |first3=Joe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Recession by sector ==\n\n=== Retail sector ===\nShopping centers around the world responded by reducing hours or closing down temporarily in response. As of 18 March 2020, the footfall to shopping centers fell by up-to 30%, with significant impact in every continent.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.aislelabs.com/blog/2020/03/23/how-shopping-centres-responding-coronavirus/  |title=How Shopping Centres Globally are Responding to Coronavirus by Aislelabs|author=Inc, Aislelabs|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> [[Simon Property Group]] became the first major US-based mall operator to close all centers on the 18th March, with government mandated closures in UAE, Italy, Germany, Spain, Brazil and Austria as of 23 March.\n\n===Transportation sector===\n{{generalize|section|date=March 2020}}\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation}}\n[[File:A nearly empty flight from PEK to LAX amid the COVID-19 pandemic 1.jpg|thumb|A nearly empty flight from [[Beijing]] to [[Los Angeles]] during the pandemic]]\n\nThe pandemic has had a significant impact on aviation industry due to [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the resulting travel restrictions]] as well as slump in demand among travelers. Significant reductions in passenger numbers has resulted in planes flying empty between airports and the cancellation of flights.\n\n=== Restaurant sector ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\nThe 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic has impacted the restaurant business. In the beginning of March 2020, some major cities in the US announced that bars and restaurants would be closed to sit-down diners and limited to [[Food delivery|takeout orders and delivery]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319091659/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some employees were fired, and more employees lacked [[sick leave]] in the sector compared to similar sectors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus exposes sick leave gap for retail, restaurant workers |url=https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/ |website=Press Enterprise |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318153437/https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nber.org/papers/w26832.pdf Sick leave] ''[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]''</ref>\n\n== Recession by country ==\n=== Australia ===\nUp to a million people have been laid off due to effects of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henriques-Gomes|first=Luke|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/24/newly-unemployed-australians-queue-at-centrelink-offices-as-mygov-website-crashes-again|title=Newly unemployed Australians queue at Centrelink offices as MyGov website crashes again|date=24 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Over 280,000 individuals applied for unemployment support at the peak day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/surge-in-demand-280-000-ask-centrelink-for-help-in-one-day-20200325-p54dwn.html|title='Surge in demand': 280,000 ask Centrelink for help in one day|last=Bonyhady|first=Nick|date=2020-03-25|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHousing prices in Australia could drop up to 20% as a result of the recession.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farrer|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/20/australian-housing-market-will-hit-the-wall-in-coronavirus-recession-experts-say|title=Australian housing market will hit the wall in coronavirus recession, experts say|date=19 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 March 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Germany ===\n\nMinister of Finance of [[Hesse]] [[Thomas Sch\u00e4fer]] was found dead on 28 March 2020. Sch\u00e4fer left a suicide note, where he mentions the \"hopeless\" economic situation in the country as one of the reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tichyseinblick.de/daili-es-sentials/zum-tod-des-hessischen-finanzministers-thomas-schaefer/|title=Zum Tod des hessischen Finanzministers Thomas Sch\u00e4fer|date=2020-03-29|website=Tichys Einblick|language=de}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\nA new record of unemployment claims was made, with 3.3 million claims made in the week ending on 21 March, with the previous record being 700,000 from 1982.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/26/21195171/new-unemployment-claims-march-21 |title=Chart: New unemployment claims soar to 3.3 million, shattering previous records|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew |date=2020-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Restaurant patronage has fallen sharply across the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local |title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business|last=Molla|first=Rani |date=16 March 2020|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> and major airlines are reducing their operations on a large scale.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/airline-news/2020/03/18/coronavirus-travel-fallout-united-jetblue-allegiant-slash-flights/2863432001/ |title=American Airlines cuts 55,000 flights, parks 450 planes amid coronavirus: 'Fight of our lives'|last=Gilbertson|first=Dawn |website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three car manufacturers]] have all halted production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/business/gm-ford-automakers-us-shut-down/index.html |title=GM, Ford and other automakers to halt production in the US|last=Business|first=Peter Valdes-Dapena and Vanessa Yurkevich, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe US [[yield curve#Inverted yield curve|yield curve inverted]] in  2019, usually indicative of a forthcoming recession.<ref>{{cite web |title=A closely followed recession indicator is flashing its most worrying sign in 12 years {{!}} Markets Insider |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644 |website=markets.businessinsider.com |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190930224654/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/yield-curve-inversion-3-month-10-year-yield-curve-inverts-2019-5-1028187644 |archivedate=September 30, 2019 |date=May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-09/u-s-yield-curve-inverts-for-the-first-time-since-march |title=U.S. Yield Curve Inverts for the First Time Since March |website=www.bloomberg.com |date=May 2019}}</ref> The [[St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index]] increased sharply from below zero<!--Feb 21--> to 5.8<!--March 20--> during March 2020.<ref name=STLFSI2blog>{{cite web |title=The St. Louis Fed's Financial Stress Index, Version 2.0 {{!}} FRED Blog |url=https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/ |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327224916/https://fredblog.stlouisfed.org/2020/03/the-st-louis-feds-financial-stress-index-version-2-0/ |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live |quote=The revised STLFSI, however, has increased sharply\u2014reminiscent of the worst of the financial market turmoil during the Great Recession in 2008-2009\u2014registering a value close to 5.8.}}</ref><ref name=STLFSI2>{{cite web |title=St. Louis Fed Financial Stress Index (STLFSI2) |url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2 |website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327222839/https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/STLFSI2 |archivedate=27 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019-nCoV}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in economics]]\n[[Category:2020 in international relations]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Recessions]]\n", "name_user": "Bitsweet55", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a short name of the recession those the name itself hasn't been used alot beside some podcast, independent new creators and one newspaper article but that up for debate.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_recession"}
{"title_page": "Pudhu Vasantham", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Pudhu Vasantham\n| image = Pudhu Vasantham DVD cover.jpg\n| caption = DVD cover\n| director = [[Vikraman]]\n| producer = [[R. B. Choudary]]<br />R. Mohan\n| writer = [[Vikraman]]\n| starring = {{unbulleted list|[[Murali (Tamil actor)|Murali]]|[[Anand Babu]]|[[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]]|[[Charle]]|[[Sithara (actress)|Sithara]]|[[Suresh (actor)|Suresh]]}}\n| music = [[S. A. Rajkumar]]\n| cinematography = A. Haribabu\n| editing = K. Thanigachalam\n| studio = [[R. B. Choudary|Super Good Films]]\n| distributor = [[R. B. Choudary|Super Good Films]]\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|1990|04|14}}\n| country = India\n| runtime = 150 minutes\n| language = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Pudhu Vasantham''''' ({{lit|New Spring}}) is a [[Tamil films of 1990|1990]] [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[drama film]], directed by [[Vikraman]] making his directorial debut,<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/films/story/19910228-with-most-films-flopping-tamil-film-industry-faces-a-bleak-future-814116-1991-02-28</ref> starring [[Murali (Tamil actor)|Murali]], [[Anand Babu]], [[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]], [[Charle]] and [[Sithara (actress)|Sithara]] in lead roles. The film, produced by [[R. B. Choudary]] and R. Mohan, had musical score by [[S. A. Rajkumar]] and was released on 14 April 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointscene.com/movies/kollywood/Puthu_Vasantham/7240 |title=Find Tamil Movie Puthu Vasantham |accessdate=2012-01-19|publisher=jointscene.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/cgi-bin/filmography/newfilmdb.cgi?name=pudhu%20vasandham\n|title=Filmography of pudhu vasantham|accessdate=2012-01-19|publisher=cinesouth.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bbthots.com/reviews/rewind/pvasantham.html Pudhu Vasantham Review]</ref> This movie is a cult classic and a lot of films have been inspired from this. The film was remade in Kannada as ''[[Shruthi (film)|Shruthi]]'' with Sunil, Honnavalli Krishna, Indudhar, Srivathsa, [[Shruti (actress)|Shruti]], Dileep and in Hindi as ''[[Baharon Ke Manzil (1991 film)|Baharon Ke Manzil]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe movie revolves around four friends, Balu (Murali), Michael (Anand Babu), Raja (Raja) and Manohar (Charle) who aim to achieve big in life despite leading a below poverty life. Balu sings well, Michael dances well, Raja plays the guitar well while Manohar plays the flute. All four friends earn their living by performing along roadsides. One day, the friends come across Gowri (Sitara), who pretends to be dumb. The four pity Gowri knowing that she is an orphan and allows her to stay with them.\n\nFriendship blossoms for Gowri with all four guys and she does all the household activities while the guys are searching for opportunities to prove their talents. One day, they see Gowri negotiating with a vegetable vendor and the four get furious knowing Gowri has cheated them by acting as a dumb girl. Gowri apologizes to them and tells a flashback.\n\nGowri is a rich girl and she falls in love with Suresh (Suresh) against her parents\u2019 wishes. As Suresh has gone abroad for a short period, Gowri preferred to stay away from her home as they would force her to marry someone of their choice. She also says that the four guys are so genuine and she liked their friendship which made her feel safe. Just to get their sympathy, she pretended to act as a dumb girl. The four guys are convinced by her reply and allow her to stay with them until Suresh returns. Gowri also sings well and the friends get an opportunity to perform at a big function. Meanwhile, Suresh returns from abroad and unites with Gowri. Now Gowri leaves to Suresh's home. Suresh, a rich man does not like Gowri making friendship with these four poor people.\n\nAlso, Suresh does not like Gowri performing on stage along with her four friends and does not permit her to sing. Gowri feels bad as she cannot help her friends which will make them lose an opportunity they had obtained. The four friends come to Suresh's house to request him to allow Gowri to perform, but he does not permit. Gowri also requests her friends to vacate the place as she cannot violate Suresh's words.\n\nNow Gowri picks up a quarrel with Suresh asking him to allow her to sing. But Suresh gets angry and doubts Gowri's relationship with her friends. Gowri feels bad that Suresh has no trust in her and also Gowri gets to know that Suresh has secretly taken her for a pregnancy test. Gowri decides to leave Suresh as he has no trust in her and joins with her friends and starts singing on stage. The movie ends showing that their friendship lasts for long as well as they have become popular.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n*[[Murali (Tamil actor)|Murali]] as Balu\n*[[Anand Babu]] as Michael\n*[[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]] as Raja\n*[[Charle]] as Manohar\n*[[Sithara (actress)|Sithara]] as Gowri\n*[[Suresh (actor)|Suresh]] as Suresh\n*[[Vinu Chakravarthy]] as Balu's father\n*[[Jaiganesh]]\n*[[Kumarimuthu]]\n*[[M. R. Krishnamurthy|MRK]]\n*[[LIC Narasimhan]]\n*[[Omakuchi Narasimhan]]\n*R. P. Viswam\n*Vijaya Chandrika\n*Jayadurga\n*Indira Devi\n*Naveena\n*Veera Raghavan\n*[[Bava Lakshmanan]]\n*[[Vijayakumar (actor)|Vijayakumar]] in a guest appearance\n*[[Manjula Vijayakumar]] in a guest appearance\n*[[K. S. Ravikumar]] as [[Security guard]] (cameo)\n{{colend}}\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Pudhu Vasantham\n| type       = [[soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[S. A. Rajkumar]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1990\n| recorded   = 1990\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 25:32\n| label      =\n| producer   = [[S. A. Rajkumar]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe film score and the soundtrack were composed by [[film composer]] [[S. A. Rajkumar]]. The soundtrack, released in 1990, features 6 tracks with lyrics written by [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]], Muthulingam and [[S. A. Rajkumar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=t0000356|title=Pudhu Vasantham Songs|accessdate=2012-01-19|publisher=raaga.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thiraipaadal.com/album.php?ALBID=ALBSAR00003|title=Pudhu Vasantham - SA. Rajkumar|accessdate=2012-01-19|publisher=thiraipaadal.com}}</ref> The song \"Paattu Onnu Paada\" is set in Sivaranjani raga.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/sivaranjani-for-pathos/article3945587.ece</ref>\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Track !! Song !! Singer(s) !! Lyrics !! Duration\n|-\n|1 || \"Aayiram Thirnaal\" || [[K. S. Chithra]], Kalyan || Muthulingham || 4:16\n|-\n|2 || \"Gowrikku Thirumanam\" || [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]] || [[S. A. Rajkumar]] || 4:27\n|-\n|3 || \"Idhu Mudhal Mudhala\" || [[S. A. Rajkumar]], [[P. Susheela]] || [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]] || 4:32\n|-\n|4 || \"Pattu Onnu Paadattuma\" || [[K. J. Yesudas|Dr. K.J Yesudas]] || rowspan=2|Muthulingham || 4:36\n|-\n|5 || \"Pattu Onnu Paada\" || S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, [[P. Susheela]] || 3:48\n|-\n|6 || \"Podu Thalam\" || S. P. Balasubrahmanyam || [[Vaali (poet)|Vaali]] || 4:11\n|-\n|7 || \"Vaarungal Vaarungal\" || K. S. Chithra, [[Mano (singer)|Mano]] || [[S. A. Rajkumar]] || 4:18\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n'''1990 [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]]'''\n* Won - [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Film]] - Pudhu Vasantham\n* Won - [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Director]] - Vikraman\n\n'''1991 [[Filmfare Awards South]]'''\n* Won - [[Filmfare Award for Best Film \u2013 Tamil|Filmfare Award for Best Film in Tamil]] - Pudhu Vasantham\n* Won - [[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director - Tamil|Filmfare Award for Best Music Director in Tamil]] - [[S. A. Rajkumar]]\n\n==Release==\n''Pudhu Vasantham'' was released on April 14, 1990 alongside another Murali starrer ''Silambu''.<ref>https://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies/slideshow/list-of-top-tamil-heroes-who-had-two-releases-on-the-same-date/murali.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Vikraman}}\n{{TamilNaduStateFilmAwardBestFilm}}\n\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:Tamil films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by S. A. Rajkumar]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vikraman]]\n[[Category:Indian buddy films]]\n[[Category:Indian musical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about composers]]\n[[Category:Films about musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Pudhu Vasantham\n| image = Pudhu Vasantham DVD cover.jpg\n| caption = DVD cover\n| director = [[Vikraman]]\n| producer = [[R. B. Choudary]]<br />R. Mohan\n| writer = [[Vikraman]]\n| starring = {{unbulleted list|[[Murali (Tamil actor)|Murali]]|[[Anand Babu]]|[[Raja (Tamil actor)|Raja]]|[[Charle]]|[[Sithara (actress)|Sithara]]|[[Suresh (actor)|Suresh]]}}\n| music = [[S. A. Rajkumar]]\n| cinematography = A. Haribabu\n| editing = K. Thanigachalam\n| studio = [[R. B. Choudary|Super Good Films]]\n| distributor = [[R. B. Choudary|Super Good Films]]\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|1990|04|14}}\n| country = India\n| runtime = 150 minutes\n| language = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Pudhu Vasantham''''' ({{lit|New Spring}}) is a [[Tamil films of 1990|1990]] [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[drama film]], directed by [[Vikraman]] making his directorial debut,<ref>https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/films/story/19910228-with-most-films-flopping-tamil-film-industry-faces-a-bleak-future-814116-1991-02-28</ref