{"title_page": "Brett Crozier", "text_new": "{{short description|United States Navy officer}}\n{{Under construction|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox military person\n|name=Brett Crozier\n|image=Brett E. Crozier (2).jpg\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1970|02|24}}\n|birth_place=[[Santa Rosa, California|Santa Rosa]], [[California]], U.S.\n|allegiance={{flag|United States}}\n|branch=[[United States Navy]]\n|rank=[[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]]\n|serviceyears=1992\u2013present\n|commands=[[VFA-94]]<br>{{USS|Blue Ridge|LCC-19}}<br>{{USS|Theodore Roosevelt|CVN-71}}\n|battles=[[Iraq War]]\n|awards=[[Legion of Merit]] (2)\n|signature=Brett Crozier signature.png\n}}\n'''Captain Brett E. Crozier''' (born February 24, 1970) is a U.S. Navy officer who until recently was the captain of the aircraft carrier [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']].<ref>{{cite web|first=Courtney|last=Kube|first2=Mosheh|last2=Gains|title=Navy relieves captain who raised alarm about coronavirus outbreak on aircraft carrier|work=[[NBC News]]|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/military/navy-expected-relieve-captain-who-raised-alarm-about-covid-19-n1175351|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/navy-relieves-uss-theodore-roosevelt-captain-loss-of-confidence-2020-4|title=US Navy fires the captain of the aircraft carrier stricken by a coronavirus outbreak|last=Pickrell|first=Ryan|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/us/captain-of-uss-roosevelt-relieved-of-command-after-letter-about-coronavirus-outbreak-was-leaked-1.624691|title=Captain of USS Roosevelt relieved of command after letter about coronavirus outbreak was leaked|website=Stars and Stripes|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/02/826317152/uss-roosevelt-commander-removed-after-criticizing-handling-of-coronavirus-outbre|title=USS Roosevelt Commander Removed After Criticizing Handling Of Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCaptain Crozier graduated from the [[United States Naval Academy]] in 1992. Following this he became a Naval Aviator and after training was assigned as a SH-60B Seahawk pilot at Barbers Point, Hawaii<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/lcc19/Pages/Bio1-9June2017-16June2018.aspx|title=Captain Brett E. Crozier|website=www.public.navy.mil|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. He received his Master\u2019s Degree in National Security and Strategic Studies from the [[Naval War College]] in 2007, and completed [[Nuclear Power School]] in 2014. <ref>https://www.public.navy.mil/airfor/cvn71/pages/commandingofficer.aspx</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn April 2014, Crozier completed the Naval Nuclear Power training program and was Executive Officer of [[USS Ronald Reagan]] (CVN 76). In June of 2017, Crozier took command of the [[USS Blue Ridge (LCC-19)|USS Blue Ridge]] in Yokosuka, Japan.\n\nCrozier was the captain of the [[aircraft carrier]] [[USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)|USS ''Theodore Roosevelt'']] until he was relieved by [[United States Secretary of the Navy|US Navy Secretary]] [[Thomas Modly]], after a letter of his complaint over infections among his crew related to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was leaked. At the time of his removal, some 114 crew members (of a total compliment of around 4,000) had been reported to be positive for the coronavirus. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52145230|title=US Navy removes captain who raised virus alarm|date=2020-04-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/02/politics/uss-roosevelt-commander-relieved/index.html|title=Commander of aircraft carrier hit by coronavirus removed for 'poor judgment' after sounding alarm|author1=Ryan Browne |author2=Zachary Cohen |author3=Jamie Crawford|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Borger|first=Julian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/02/us-navy-uss-theodore-roosevelt-coronavirus|title=US navy fires commander who raised alarm about coronavirus on ship|date=2020-04-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Honors, awards, and decorations ==\n{| style=\"margin-left:auto; margin-right:auto;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" |[[File:Naval Aviator Badge.jpg|220px|center]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=5|type=award-oak|ribbon=Defense Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Air Medal ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Service Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -75px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:1 golden star.svg|23px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -53px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:1 golden star.svg|23px]]</span>\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=award-star|ribbon=Navy and Marine Corps Achievement ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribb