{"title_page": "Hannah McFadden", "text_new": "{{short description|American Paralympic athlete}}\n{{infobox sportsperson\n| image            = 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships - 26072013 - Hannah McFadden of USA during the Women's 400m - T54 second semifinal.jpg\n| nationality      = <!--[[United States]]-->\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1996|01|23}}<ref name=pro>{{cite web|url=https://www.teamusa.org/para-track-and-field/athletes/Hannah-McFadden|title=Hannah McFadden}}</ref>\n| height           = 5 ft 3 in<ref name=pro/>\n| weight           = 117 lbs<ref name=pro/>\n| country          = [[United States]]\n| sport            = [[Track and field]]\n| disability_class = [[T54 (classification)|T54]]\n| event            = [[100m]], [[200m]], [[400m]]\n| worlds           = \n'''2013'''<ref name=100m2013t54>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/video/athletics-womens-100m-t54-final-2013-ipc-athletics-world-championships-lyon|title=Athletics - women's 100m T54 final - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships, Lyon}}</ref>\n: 100m, 6th\n\n'''2015'''<ref name=pro/>\n: 100m, {{bronze medal}}\n: 200m, {{bronze medal}}\n\n'''2017'''<ref name=pro/>\n: 100m, {{bronze medal}}\n: 200m, {{bronze medal}}\n: 400m, 7th\n| paralympics      =\n'''2012'''<ref name=pro/>\n: 100m, 8th\n\n'''2016'''<ref name=pro/>\n: 100m, 4th\n: 400m, 7th\n}}\n\n'''Hannah McFadden''' (born January 23, 1996) is an [[Albanian Americans|Albanian-American]] [[Paralympic]] [[sprint (running)|sprinter]]. She is the adopted daughter of [[Deborah McFadden]] and the sister of multiple-time [[Summer Paralympic Games]] gold medalist [[Tatyana McFadden]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/disability-43865306</ref>\n\nWhen she competed with her sister at the [[2012 Summer Paralympic Games]], it was the first time that two siblings had ever competed together in a Paralympic Games.<ref name=pro/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.teamusa.org/News/2015/October/15/Hannah-McFadden-Is-Ready-To-Make-A-Name-For-Herself \"Hannah McFadden Is Ready To Make A Name For Herself\"]\n* [https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/rio-2016/2016/06/29/hannah-mcfadden-sprints-out-sisters-shadow/86528656/ \"Hannah McFadden sprints out of sister's shadow\"]\n* {{IPC athlete|id=hannah-mcfadden|old_id=966416}}\n* {{Team USA|MC/Hannah-McFadden}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFadden, Hannah}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes from Maryland]]\n\n\n{{US-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Paralympic athlete}}\n{{infobox sportsperson\n| image            = 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships - 26072013 - Hannah McFadden of USA during the Women's 400m - T54 second semifinal.jpg\n| nationality      = <!--[[United States]]-->\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1996|01|23}}<ref name=pro>{{cite web|url=https://www.teamusa.org/para-track-and-field/athletes/Hannah-McFadden|title=Hannah McFadden}}</ref>\n| height           = 5 ft 3 in<ref name=pro/>\n| weight           = 117 lbs<ref name=pro/>\n| country          = [[United States]]\n| sport            = [[Track and field]]\n| disability_class = [[T54 (classification)|T54]]\n| event            = [[100m]], [[200m]], [[400m]]\n| worlds           = \n'''2013'''<ref name=100m2013t54>{{cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/video/athletics-womens-100m-t54-final-2013-ipc-athletics-world-championships-lyon|title=Athletics - women's 100m T54 final - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships, Lyon}}</ref>\n: 100m, 6th\n\n'''2015'''<ref name=pro/>\n: 100m, {{bronze medal}}\n: 200m, {{bronze medal}}\n\n'''2017'''<ref name=pro/>\n: 100m, {{bronze medal}}\n: 200m, {{bronze medal}}\n: 400m, 7th\n| paralympics      =\n'''2012'''<ref name=pro/>\n: 100m, 8th\n\n'''2016'''<ref name=pro/>\n: 100m, 4th\n: 400m, 7th\n}}\n\n'''Hannah McFadden''' (born January 23, 1996) is an [[Albanian Americans|Albanian-American]] [[Paralympic]] [[sprint (running)|sprinter]]. She is the adopted daughter of [[Deborah McFadden]] and the sister of multiple-time [[Summer Paralympic Games]] gold medalist [[Tatyana McFadden]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/disability-43865306</ref>\n\nWhen she competed with her sister at the [[2012 Summer Paralympic Games]], it was the first time that two siblings had ever competed together in a Paralympic Games.<ref name=pro/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.teamusa.org/News/2015/October/15/Hannah-McFadden-Is-Ready-To-Make-A-Name-For-Herself \"Hannah McFadden Is Ready To Make A Name For Herself\"]\n* [https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/rio-2016/2016/06/29/hannah-mcfadden-sprints-out-sisters-shadow/86528656/ \"Hannah McFadden sprints out of sister's shadow\"]\n* {{IPC athlete|966416}}\n* {{Team USA|MC/Hannah-McFadden}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFadden, Hannah}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American female sprinters]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes from Maryland]]\n\n\n{{US-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hannah_McFadden"}
{"title_page": "Dharavi", "text_new": "{{About|the locality in Mumbai|other uses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = |settlement_type\n| image_skyline                   = File:Dharavi slum in Mumbai, India August 2009 4.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Dharavi slum in 2009\n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Mumbai\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|19.040208|N|72.85085|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = Metro\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Mumbai]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 2.165\n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_density_km2          = 277,136.3 \u2013 461,893.8\n| population_est                  = 600,000 \u2013 1,000,000\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2016\n| literacy rate                   = 83.13 (as per 2001 census)\n| demographics_type1              = Language\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN CODE]]\n| postal_code                     = 400017\n| area_code                       = 022\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone Code\n| registration_plate              = MH-01\n| blank1_name_sec1                = Civic agency\n| blank1_info_sec1                = [[Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation|BMC]]\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n[[Image:Principaux Bidonvilles.png|225px|Dharavi compared to other large slums in the world. Map according to [[Mike Davis (scholar)|Mike Davis]].|thumb|right]]\n\n'''Dharavi''' is a [[locality (settlement)|locality]] in [[Mumbai]], Maharashtra, India, considered to be one of the world's largest [[Slum|slums]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Dharavi-in-Mumbai-is-no-longer-Asias-largest-slum/articleshow/9119450.cms|publisher=Times of India|access-date=9 November 2018|year=2011|title=Dharavi in Mumbai is no longer Asia's largest slum|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111002239/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Dharavi-in-Mumbai-is-no-longer-Asias-largest-slum/articleshow/9119450.cms|archive-date=11 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The next billion users : digital life beyond the West|last=Arora|first=Payal|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=2019|isbn=9780674983786|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=75|oclc=1057240289}}</ref> Dharavi has an area of just over {{convert|2.1|km2|sqmi acre}}<ref name=\"Shanty-towns emerge targets for development\">{{cite news |url=http://www.livemint.com/Money/1V0Zs8oNNvbAWEP6xHQQzN/Shantytowns-emerge-targets-for-development.html |title=Shanty-towns emerge targets for development |work=Livemint |access-date=27 December 2016 |date=6 July 2007 |author=Gayatri Ramanathan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119202545/http://www.livemint.com/Money/1V0Zs8oNNvbAWEP6xHQQzN/Shantytowns-emerge-targets-for-development.html |archive-date=19 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a population of about 700,000. With a [[population density]] of over {{pop density|600000|2.165|km2|sqmi|prec=0}}, Dharavi is one of the most densely populated areas in the world. \n\nThe Dharavi slum was founded in 1884 during the British colonial era, and grew in part because of an expulsion of factories and residents from the peninsular city centre by the colonial government, and from the migration of poor rural Indians into urban Mumbai. For this reason, Dharavi is currently a highly multi-religious, multi-ethnic, and diverse settlement.<ref name=\"Sharma, Kalpana 2000\">Sharma, Kalpana; \"Rediscovering Dharavi: Story From Asia's Largest Slum\" (2000) \u2013 Penguin Books {{ISBN|0-14-100023-6}}</ref>\n\nDharavi has an active informal economy in which numerous household enterprises employ many of the slum residents{{ndash}}<ref name=\"Ahmed\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7676337.stm | work=BBC News | title=Indian slum hit by New York woes | date=20 October 2008 | accessdate=1 May 2010 | first=Zubair | last=Ahmed | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023153647/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7676337.stm | archive-date=23 October 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> leather, textiles and pottery products are among the goods made inside Dharavi. The total annual turnover has been estimated at over {{USD}}1 billion.<ref name=\"nyenrode\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nyenrode.nl/businesstopics/europeindia/Pages/%E2%80%9CJaiHo%E2%80%9DDharavi.aspx |title=Jai Ho Dharavi |publisher=Nyenrode Business Universiteit |accessdate=5 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531175111/http://www.nyenrode.nl/businesstopics/europeindia/Pages/%E2%80%9CJaiHo%E2%80%9DDharavi.aspx |archive-date=31 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDharavi has suffered from many epidemics and other disasters, asincluding a widespread plague in 1896 which killed over half of the population of Mumbai.<ref name=\"Swaminathan, M. 1995\">Swaminathan, M. (1995). Aspects of urban poverty in Bombay. Environment and Urbanization, 7(1), 133\u2013144</ref> Though large sums of money have been borrowed by the Indian government in the guise of improving sanitation in Dharavi, none of these have materialized into any development on the ground.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Mumbai Slum Sanitation Program \u2013 Partnering with Slum Communities for SustainableSanitation in a Megalopolis |date=1 September 2006 |publisher=World bank |location=Washington |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/620841468041130033/pdf/384560IN0Mumbai0slum01PUBLIC1.pdf |accessdate=15 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815152603/http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/620841468041130033/pdf/384560IN0Mumbai0slum01PUBLIC1.pdf |archive-date=15 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\n<br />\n\n==Dharavi History==\nIn the 18th century, Dharavi was an island with a predominantly mangrove swamp.<ref name=\"origins\">{{cite book|last=D'Cunha|first=Jose Gerson|title=The Origins of Bombay|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=Bombay|year=1900|edition=3|page=265|chapter=IV The Portuguese Period|isbn=978-81-206-0815-3|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=miD5YO05jpUC&dq=the+origins+of+bombay|access-date=4 January 2009}}</ref> It was a sparsely populated village before the late 19th century, inhabited by [[Koli people|Koli]] fishermen.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{Cite news | url = http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/ | title = Dharavi Mumbai's Shadow City | author = Mark Jacobson | work = [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] | date = May 2007 | access-date = 30 April 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081121103109/http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/ | archive-date = 21 November 2008 | url-status = dead | author-link = The Lampshade: A Holocaust Detective Story from Buchenwald to New Orleans }}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = Globalization and Community, Volume 23 : Durable Slum : Dharavi and the Right to Stay Put in Globalizing Mumbai|last = Weinstein|first = Liza|publisher = University of Minnesota Press|date = June 2014|isbn = 9780816683109|location = Minneapolis, MN, USA|pages = 5}}</ref> Dharavi was then referred to as the village of [[Koliwada]].<ref name=jn2010/>\n\n===Colonial era===\nMumbai has been one of the centers of India's urbanization for 200 years. In the 1850s, after decades of urban growth under [[East India Company]] and [[British Raj]], the city's population reached half a million. The urban area then covered mostly the southern extension of Mumbai peninsula, the population density was over 10 times higher than London at that time.<ref name=jn2010>Jan Nijman, A STUDY OF SPACE IN MUMBAI'S SLUMS, Tijdschrift Voor economic en social geographies, Volume 101, Issue 1, pages 4\u201317, February 2010</ref>\n\n[[File:Shanty dwellings, Railway tracks and Mosque in Dharavi Slum Mumbai India February 2010.jpg|thumb|left|Shanty dwellings next to railway tracks in Dharavi (about 2010). A mosque inside the slum is visible. The railway network provides mass transit to the slum residents.]]\nThe most polluting industries were tanneries, and the first tannery moved from peninsular Mumbai into Dharavi in 1887. People who worked with leather, typically a profession of lowest Hindu castes and of Muslim Indians, moved into Dharavi. Other early settlers included the Kumbars, a large Gujarati community of potters (another polluting industry). The colonial government granted them a 99-year land-lease in 1895. Rural migrants looking for jobs poured into Mumbai, and its population soared past 1 million. Other artisans, like the [[embroidery]] workers from [[Uttar Pradesh]], started the ready-made garments trade.<ref name=\"NatGeo\"/> These industries created jobs, labor moved in, but there was no government effort to plan or invest in any infrastructure in or near Dharavi. The living quarters and small scale factories grew haphazardly, without provision for sanitation, drains, safe drinking water, roads or other basic services. But some ethnic, caste and religious communities that have settled in Dharavi at that time helped build the settlement of Dharavi, by forming organizations and political parties, building school and temples, constructing homes and factories.<ref name=\":0\" /> Dharavi's first mosque, Badi Masjid, started in 1887 and the oldest Hindu temple, Ganesh Mandir, was built in 1913.<ref name=jn2010/>\n\n===Post-independence===\nAt India's independence from colonial rule in 1947, Dharavi had grown to be the largest slum in Mumbai and all of India. It still had a few empty spaces, which continued to serve as waste-dumping grounds for operators across the city.<ref name=jn2010/> Mumbai, meanwhile, continued to grow as a city. Soon Dharavi was surrounded by the city, and became a key hub for informal economy.<ref>, Eyre, L. (1990), The shanty towns of central Bombay. Urban Geography 11, pages 130\u2013152</ref> Starting from the 1950s, proposals for Dharavi redevelopment plans periodically came out, but most of these plans failed because of lack of financial banking and/or political support.<ref name=\":0\" /> Dharavi's Co-operative Housing Society was formed in the 1960s to uplift the lives of thousands of slum dwellers by the initiative of Shri. M.V. Duraiswamy, a well-known social worker and congress leader of that region. The society promoted 338 flats and 97 shops and was named as Dr. Baliga Nagar. By the late 20th century, Dharavi occupied about {{convert|432|acre|ha|order=flip}}, with an astounding population density of more than 2900 people per hectare (1200/acre).<ref name=jn2010/><ref>Graber et al. (2005), Living and working in slums of Mumbai. Working paper 36. Magdeburg: Otto-von-Guericke Universitat, Netherlands</ref>\n\n=== Redevelopment plans ===\n[[Image:Pottery unit in Dharavi, Mumbai.jpg|thumb|left|A traditional pottery unit in Dharavi.]]\n\n[[File:Dharavi slum in Mumbai, India August 2009 3.jpg|thumb|left|Street vendors and farmers market along the road passing through Dharavi slum in Mumbai.]]\nThere have been many plans since 1997 to redevelop Dharavi like the former slums of Hong Kong such as [[Tai Hang]]. In 2004, the cost of redevelopment was estimated to be {{IRs|5000|c}}.<ref name=\"economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/Calls-to-scrap-Dharavi-makeover-gain-ground/articleshow/6363548.cms | work=The Times of India | title=Calls to scrap Dharavi makeover gain ground | date=20 August 2010 | access-date=3 November 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925015929/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/Calls-to-scrap-Dharavi-makeover-gain-ground/articleshow/6363548.cms | archive-date=25 September 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref> Companies from around the world have bid to redevelop Dharavi,<ref name=\"livemint.com\">{{cite web |author=Madhurima Nandy |url=http://www.livemint.com/2010/04/23222011/US-firm-exits-Dharavi-project.html?d=1 |title=US firm exits Dharavi project citing delays |publisher=Livemint |date=23 April 2010 |accessdate=7 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916195031/http://www.livemint.com/2010/04/23222011/US-firm-exits-Dharavi-project.html?d=1 |archive-date=16 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> including [[Lehman Brothers]], Dubai's Limitless and Singapore's Capitaland Ltd.<ref name=\"livemint.com\"/> In 2010, it was estimated to cost {{IRs|15000|c}} to redevelop.<ref name=\"economictimes.indiatimes.com\"/>\n\nThe latest urban [[redevelopment]] plan proposed for the Dharavi area is managed by American-trained architect Mukesh Mehta<ref name=\"NatGeo\"/> The plan involves the construction of {{convert|30000000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of [[houses|housing]], schools, parks and roads to serve the 57,000 families residing in the area, along with {{convert|40000000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of residential and commercial space for sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/UnouoCTZDd8YLPeRrethTP/Dharavi-redevelopment-plan-is-robbing-us-of-space-residents.html|title=Dharavi redevelopment plan is robbing us of space: residents|date=5 September 2007|publisher=Live Mint|accessdate=7 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210194254/http://www.livemint.com/Politics/UnouoCTZDd8YLPeRrethTP/Dharavi-redevelopment-plan-is-robbing-us-of-space-residents.html|archive-date=10 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> There is still a significant local opposition to the plans, largely because existing residents still feel {{convert|350|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of revised permanent alternate accommodation per tenant is not adequate each. Furthermore, only those families who lived in the area before 2000 are slated for resettlement. Concerns have also been raised by residents who fear that some of their small businesses in the \"informal\" sector may not be relocated under the redevelopment plan. Due to this opposition, a trust has been proposed called the Dharavi Community Land Trust that will be made up of community members, landowners, and neighborhood associations.\n\nIn 2008 German students Jens Kaercher and Lucas Schwind won a Next Generation prize for their innovative redevelopment strategy designed to protect the current residents from needing to relocate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lafargeholcim-foundation.org/projects/realizing-solutions-for-the-redevelopment-of-dharavi-mumbai-in|title=Realizing solutions for the redevelopment of Dharavi, Mumbai, In|last=info@lafargeholcim-foundation.org|first=LafargeHolcim Foundation for Sustainable Construction|website=LafargeHolcim Foundation website|access-date=20 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820235021/https://www.lafargeholcim-foundation.org/projects/realizing-solutions-for-the-redevelopment-of-dharavi-mumbai-in|archive-date=20 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOther redevelopment schemes include the \"Dharavi Masterplan\" devised by British architectural and engineering firm Foster + Partners, that proposes \"double-height spaces that create an intricate vertical landscape and reflect the community\u2019s way of life\" built-in phases that the firm says would \"eliminate the need for transit camps,\" instead catalyzing the rehabilitation of Dharavi \"from within.\"\n\nA Dubai based firm \u2013 SecLink group has planned to redevelop the slum into a completely new area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/dubai-firm-to-transform-asias-biggest-slum-1.62097740|title=Dubai firm to transform Asia's biggest slum|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=12 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412182103/https://gulfnews.com/business/dubai-firm-to-transform-asias-biggest-slum-1.62097740|archive-date=12 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On setting up of the SPV, the private firm will have to bring in the equity of Rs 400 crore, while the state government will invest another Rs 100 crore. The company planning to do it is also building infrastructure and affordable housing projects in Singapore and Dubai. Following the empowered committee\u2019s nod, the senior state officials said that an MoU will soon be executed between the state government, and the Dharavi Redevelopment Project Authority (DRPA) and the company. With an almost estimated cost of over Rs 26,000 crore, the Dharavi makeover project is the biggest brownfield redevelopment project in India. To make the redevelopment more economically viable, the state government\u2019s plan is involving transforming the region into a hub for commercial and business activity. Dharavi is close to the Bandra Kurla Complex, which is India\u2019s richest business district, and one of the richest in Asia.\n\n==Demographics==\nThe total current population of Dharavi slum is unknown, and estimates vary widely. Some sources suggest it is 300,000<ref name=claralewis>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-06/india/29742525_1_largest-slum-dharavi-nivara-hakk-sangharsh-samiti Dharavi in Mumbai is no longer Asia's largest slum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025211607/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-06/india/29742525_1_largest-slum-dharavi-nivara-hakk-sangharsh-samiti |date=25 October 2013 }} Clara Lewis, The Times of India (6 July 2011)</ref><ref name=\"Slums: The case of Mumbai, India\">[http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dpu-projects/Global_Report/pdfs/Mumbai.pdf Slums: The case of Mumbai, India] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403122230/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dpu-projects/Global_Report/pdfs/Mumbai.pdf |date=3 April 2018 }} Neelima Risbud, School of Planning and Architecture, New Delhi, India</ref> to about a million.<ref name=jimyardley>[http://www.deccanherald.com/content/216254/dharavi-self-created-special-economic.html Dharavi: Self-created special economic zone for the poor] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717231402/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/216254/dharavi-self-created-special-economic.html |date=17 July 2017 }} Jim Yardley, Deccan Herald (2010)</ref> With Dharavi spread over {{convert|500|acre|ha|order=flip}}, it is also estimated to have a population density of an incredible 869,565 people per square mile. With a literacy rate of 69%, Dharavi is the most literate slum in India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_mumbai-s-slums-are-india-s-most-literate_1015111 |title=Mumbai's slums are India's most literate \u2013 Mumbai \u2013 DNA |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date=27 February 2006 |accessdate=16 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728070119/http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_mumbai-s-slums-are-india-s-most-literate_1015111 |archive-date=28 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAbout 30% of the population of Dharavi is Muslim, compared to 13% average population of Muslims in India.<ref>[http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2007/05/dharavi-mumbai-slum/jonas-bendiksen-photography Dharavi: Mumbai's Shadow City] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214214727/http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2007/05/dharavi-mumbai-slum/jonas-bendiksen-photography |date=14 February 2018 }} National Geographic (2007)</ref><ref>[http://censusindia.gov.in/Census_And_You/religion.aspx Census Data: India] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315004939/http://censusindia.gov.in/Census_And_You/religion.aspx |date=15 March 2018 }} Government of India</ref> The Christian population is estimated to be about 6%,<ref>[http://nazrene.org/dharavi_deanery.html History of Dharavi churches] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127042243/http://nazrene.org/dharavi_deanery.html |date=27 November 2013 }} Dharavi Deanery (2011)</ref> while the rest are predominantly Hindus (63%), with some Buddhists and other minority religions. Among the Hindus, about 20% work on animal skin production, tanneries and leather goods. Other Hindus specialise in pottery work, textile goods manufacturing, retail and trade, distilleries and other caste professions \u2013 all of these as small-scale household operations. The slum residents are from all over India, people who migrated from rural regions of many different states.<ref>Sharma, Kalpana (2000). Rediscovering Dharavi: Stories from Asia's largest slum. Penguin Books India; {{ISBN|978-0141000237}}</ref> The slum has numerous mosques, temples and churches to serve people of Islam, Hindu and Christian faiths; with Badi Masjid, a mosque, as the oldest religious structure in Dharavi.\n\n==Location and characteristics==\n[[File:Bombaywardsmap''H-E''.PNG|thumb|220px|Dharavi is located in Ward H East, marked in dark blue, one of the many [[Administrative divisions of Mumbai|British-era administrative wards]] of Mumbai city limits (yellow). Dharavi is southern end of Ward H East, and other residential and commercial areas in the Ward marked in dark blue include [[Santacruz, Mumbai|Santacruz]], [[Vile Parle]] and [[Mahim]].]]\nDharavi is a large area situated between Mumbai's two main suburban railway lines, the Western and Central Railways. To the west of Dharavi are [[Mahim]] and [[Bandra]], and to the north lies the [[Mithi River]]. The Mithi River empties into the [[Arabian Sea]] through the [[Mahim Creek]]. The area of [[Antop Hill]] lies to the east while the locality called [[Matunga]] is located in the South. Due to its location and poor sewage and drainage systems, Dharavi particularly becomes vulnerable to floods during the [[wet season]].\n\nDharavi is considered one of the largest slums in the world. The low-rise building style and narrow street structure of the area make Dharavi very cramped and confined. Like most slums, it is overpopulated. Compared to Mumbai's urban [[floor space index]] (FSI) of a range from 5 to 15, in Dharavi it is about 13.3 [[citation needed]]. Government officials are considering changing the Dharavi's floor space index to 4. Despite the expensive Mumbai lifestyle, Dharavi provides a cheap alternative where rent is as low as Rs.1000 per month.\n\n==Economy==\n[[Image:An embroidery unit in Dharavi, Mumbai.jpg|thumb|left|An embroidery unit in Dharavi.]]\nIn addition to the traditional [[pottery]] and textile industries in Dharavi,<ref name=\"natgeo\"/> there is an increasingly large [[recycling]] industry, processing recyclable waste from other parts of [[Mumbai]]. Recycling in Dharavi is reported to employ approximately 250,000 people.<ref name=\"gua\" /> While recycling is a major industry in the neighborhood, it is also reported to be a source of heavy pollution in the area.<ref name=\"gua\" /> The district has an estimated 5000 businesses<ref>{{cite web |author=Madhurima Nandy |url=http://www.livemint.com/2010/03/23000503/Harvard-students-get-lessons-o.html?d=1 |title=Harvard students get lessons on Dharavi |publisher=Livemint |date=23 March 2010 |accessdate=7 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918192410/http://www.livemint.com/2010/03/23000503/Harvard-students-get-lessons-o.html?d=1 |archive-date=18 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and 15,000 single-room factories.<ref name=\"gua\">[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/world/story/0,,2026024,00.html Waste not, want not in the \u00a3700m slum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106102248/http://observer.guardian.co.uk/world/story/0,,2026024,00.html |date=6 January 2008 }}, ''The Guardian'', 4 March 2007</ref> Two major suburban railways feed into Dharavi, making it an important commuting station for people in the area going to and from work.\n\nDharavi exports goods around the world.<ref name=\"Ahmed\"/> Often these consist of various leather products, jewellery, various accessories, and textiles. Markets for Dharavi's goods include stores in the United States, Europe, and the Middle East.<ref name=\"Ahmed\" /> The total (and largely informal economy) turnover is estimated to be between {{USD}}500 million,<ref name=\"nyenrode\"/> over {{USD}}650 million per year,<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/world/06/dharavi_slum/html/dharavi_slum_intro.stm|title = Dharavi|publisher = BBC|accessdate = 2 January 2010|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100906022807/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/world/06/dharavi_slum/html/dharavi_slum_intro.stm|archive-date = 6 September 2010|url-status = live}}</ref> to over {{USD}}1 billion per year.<ref name=\"gua\"/> The per capita income of the residents, depending on estimated population range of 300,000 to about 1 million, ranges between US$500 to US$2000 per year.\n\nA few travel operators offer guided tours through Dharavi, showing the industrial and the residential part of Dharavi and explaining about the problems and challenges Dharavi is facing. These tours give a deeper insight into a slum in general and Dharavi in particular.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/travel/destinations/india/article7124205.ece|title=Mumbai slum tour: why you should see Dharavi|accessdate=7 November 2012|publisher=Timesonline.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522184950/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/travel/destinations/india/article7124205.ece|archive-date=22 May 2010|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n== Utility services ==\nPotable water is supplied by the [[Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation|MCGM]] to Dharavi and the whole of Mumbai. However, a large amount of water is lost due to water thefts, illegal connection and leakage.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Now, a toll-free helpline to check water leakage, theft \u2013 Indian Express|url = http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/now-a-tollfree-helpline-to-check-water-lea/531630/|website = archive.indianexpress.com|publisher = |accessdate = 8 December 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150904001826/http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/now-a-tollfree-helpline-to-check-water-lea/531630/|archive-date = 4 September 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> The community also has a number of water wells that are sources of non-potable water.\n\n\nCooking gas is supplied in the form of [[Liquefied petroleum gas|liquefied petroleum gas cylinders]] sold by state-owned oil companies,<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-cooking-gas-cylinders-to-be-sold-at-petrol-pumps-1865090|title = Cooking gas cylinders to be sold at petrol pumps|date = 24 July 2013|work = Daily News and Analysis.|access-date = 8 December 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150615204630/http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-cooking-gas-cylinders-to-be-sold-at-petrol-pumps-1865090|archive-date = 15 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> as well as through [[Natural gas|piped natural gas]] supplied by Mahanagar Gas Limited.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-piped-gas-becomes-more-attractive-for-the-kitchen-1740662|title = Piped gas becomes more attractive for the kitchen|date = 14 September 2012|work = Daily News and Analysis|access-date = |via = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150615203513/http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-piped-gas-becomes-more-attractive-for-the-kitchen-1740662|archive-date = 15 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThere are settlement houses that still do not have legal connections to the utility service and thus rely on illegal connection to the water and power supply which means a water and power shortage for the residents in Dharavi.\n\n===Sanitation issues===\n[[Image:Dharavi Slum in Mumbai.jpg|thumb|Inside Dharavi]]\n[[File:Mumbai 03-2016 49 Dharavi near Mahim Junction.jpg|thumb|Mosque in Dharavi]]\nDharavi has severe problems with public health. Water access derives from public standpipes stationed throughout the slum. Additionally, with the limited lavatories they have, they are extremely filthy and broken down to the point of being unsafe. Mahim Creek is a local river that is widely used by local residents for urination and defecation causing the spread of contagious diseases.<ref name=\"natgeo\"/> The open sewers in the city drain to the creek causing a spike in water pollutants, septic conditions, and foul odors. Due to the air pollutants, diseases such as lung cancer, tuberculosis, and asthma are common among residents. There are government proposals in regards to improving Dharavi's sanitation issues. The residents have a section where they wash their clothes in water that people defecate in. This spreads the amount of disease as doctors have to deal with over 4,000 cases of typhoid a day. There is also an average of 1 toilet per 500 people.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Epidemics and other disasters==\nDharavi has experienced a long history of epidemics and natural disasters, sometimes with significant loss of lives. The first plague to devastate Dharavi, along with other settlements of Mumbai, happened in 1896, when nearly half of the population died. A series of plagues and other epidemics continued to affect Dharavi, and Mumbai in general, for the next 25 years, with high rates of mortality.<ref>Gandy, M. (2008), Landscapes of disaster: water, modernity, and urban fragmentation in Mumbai. Environment and planning. A, 40(1), 108</ref><ref>Renapurkar, D. M. (1988). Distribution and Susceptibility of Xenopsylla astia to DDT in Maharashtra State, India. International Journal of Tropical Insect Science, 9(03), 377\u2013380</ref> [[Dysentery]] epidemics have been common throughout the years and explained by the high population density of Dharavi. Other reported epidemics include [[Typhoid fever|typhoid]], [[cholera]], [[leprosy]], [[amoebiasis]] and [[polio]].<ref name=\"Swaminathan, M. 1995\"/><ref>[http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/09/12/india-restarts-battle-against-leprosy/?_r=0 India Restarts Battle Against Leprosy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323021706/http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/09/12/india-restarts-battle-against-leprosy/?_r=0 |date=23 March 2014 }} Anjali Thomas, New York Times (12 September 2013)</ref> For example, in 1986, a cholera epidemic was reported, where most patients were children of Dharavi. Typical patients to arrive in hospitals were in late and critical care condition, and the mortality rates were abnormally high.<ref>Mehta et al., An outbreak of cholera in children of Bombay slums, Journal of Diarrhoeal Diseases Research, June 4(2): page 94</ref> In recent years, cases of drug resistant [[tuberculosis]] have been reported in Dharavi.<ref>Udwadia, Z. F., Pinto, L. M., & Uplekar, M. W. (2010). Tuberculosis management by private practitioners in Mumbai, India: has anything changed in two decades?. PLoS One, 5(8), e12023</ref><ref>Loewenberg, S. (2012), India reports cases of totally drug-resistant tuberculosis, The Lancet, 379(9812), 205</ref>\n\nFires and other disasters are common. For example, in January 2013, a fire destroyed many slum properties and caused injuries.<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dharavi-turns-into-fireball-as-flames-engulf-slum/1063044/ Dharavi turns into fireball as flames engulf slum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125011615/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dharavi-turns-into-fireball-as-flames-engulf-slum/1063044 |date=25 January 2013 }} Indian Express (22 January 2013)</ref> In 2005, massive floods caused deaths and extensive property damage.<ref>Samaddar, S., Misra, B. A., Chatterjee, R., & Tatano, H. (2012). [http://idrim.ir/index.php/idrim/article/viewFile/38/pdf_11 Understanding Community\u2019s Evacuation Intention Development Process in a Flood Prone Micro-hotspot]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Mumbai. IDRiM Journal, 2(2)</ref>\n\nThe [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]] also affected the slum. The first case was reported in April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Joshi |first1=Sahil |title=First coronavirus case reported from Mumbai's Dharavi slum |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/first-coronavirus-positive-case-reported-from-dharavi-in-mumbai-1662265-2020-04-01 |website=India Today |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==In the media==\n{{Quote\n |quote    = From the main road leading through Dharavi, the place makes a desperate impression. However, once having entered the narrow lanes Dharavi proves that the prejudice of slums as dirty, underdeveloped, and criminal places does not fit real living conditions. Sure, communal sanitation blocks that are mostly in a miserable condition and overcrowded space do not comfort the living. Inside the huts, it is, however, very clean, and some huts share some elements of beauty. Nice curtains at the windows and balconies covered by flowers and plants indicate that people try to arrange their homes as cosy and comfortable as possible.\n |source   = Denis Gruber et al. (2005)<ref>Denis Gruber, Andrea Kirschner, Sandra Mill, Manuela Schach, Steffen Schmekel, and Hardo Seligman, Living and Working in Slums of Mumbai, Otto-von-Guericke-Universit\u00e4t Magdeburg, Institut f\u00fcr Soziologie, Magdeburg, Germany, {{ISSN|1615-8229}} (April 2005)</ref>\n |width    = 125%\n |fontsize = 100%\n |bgcolor  = #CEECC2\n |align    = center\n}}\nDharavi was most notably used as the backdrop in the film ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mendes|first=Ana Cristina|date=2010|title=Showcasing India Unshining: Film Tourism in Danny Boyle'sSlumdog Millionaire|journal=Third Text|language=en|volume=24|issue=4|pages=471\u2013479|doi=10.1080/09528822.2010.491379|issn=0952-8822}}</ref> It has also been depicted in a number of Indian films, including ''[[Deewaar]]'' (1975), ''[[Nayakan]]'' (1987), ''[[Salaam Bombay!]]'' (1988), ''[[Parinda]]'' (1989), ''[[Dharavi (film)|Dharavi]]'' (1991), ''[[Bombay (film)|Bombay]]'' (1995), [[Ram Gopal Varma]]'s \"[[Ram Gopal Varma#Indian gangster trilogy|Indian Gangster Trilogy]]\" (1998\u20132005), the ''[[Sarkar (2005 film)|Sarkar]]'' series (2005\u20132008), ''[[Footpath (2003 film)|Footpath]]'' (2003), ''[[Black Friday (2004 film)|Black Friday]]'' (2004), ''[[No Smoking (2007 film)|No Smoking]]'' (2007), ''[[Traffic Signal (film)|Traffic Signal]]'' (2007), ''[[Aamir (film)|Aamir]]'' (2008), ''[[Mankatha]]'' (2011), ''[[Thuppakki]]'' (2012), ''[[Thalaivaa]]'' (2013), ''[[Bhoothnath Returns]]'' (2014), ''[[Kaala (2018 film)|Kaala]]'' (2018) and ''[[Gully Boy]]'' (2019).\n\n''Dharavi, Slum for Sale'' (2009) by Lutz Konermann and Rob Appleby is a German [[Documentary film|documentary]].<ref>{{IMDb title|1188984|Dharavi, Slum for Sale}}</ref> In a programme aired in the United Kingdom in January 2010, [[Kevin McCloud]] and Channel 4 aired a two-part series titled ''Slumming It''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/4homes/on-tv/kevin-mccloud-slumming-it/kevin-mccloud-slumming-it-episode-two-10-01-06_p_1.html |title=Slumming It: Dharavi |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=8 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118083854/http://www.channel4.com/4homes/on-tv/kevin-mccloud-slumming-it/kevin-mccloud-slumming-it-episode-two-10-01-06_p_1.html |archive-date=18 January 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> which centered around Dharavi and its inhabitants. The poem \"[[Blessing (poem)|Blessing]]\" by [[Imtiaz Dharker]] is about Dharavi not having enough water. ''[[For The Win]]'', by [[Cory Doctorow]], is partially set in Dharavi. In 2014, Belgian researcher Katrien Vankrunkelsven made a 22-minute film on Dharavi which is entitled ''The Way of Dharavi''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s_0X0wIvqVM|title=Documentary \u2013 The Way Of Dharavi 2014|last=Sse Productions bvba|date=3 April 2015|publisher=|access-date=30 April 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017233205/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s_0X0wIvqVM|archive-date=17 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Poverty in India]]\n* [[List of slums in India]]\n* [[Urbanisation in India]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n*Dharavi: Documenting Informalities. Practical Action June 2018. Jonatan Habib Engqvist and Maria Lantz. {{ISBN|978-1853397103}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{commons category}}\n* Sharma, Kalpana; \"Rediscovering Dharavi: Story From Asia's Largest Slum\" (2000) \u2013 Penguin Books {{ISBN|0-14-100023-6}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/world/06/dharavi_slum/html/dharavi_slum_intro.stm \"Life in a Slum\" \u2013 BBC News]\n* {{Cite news | url = http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/ | title = Dharavi Mumbai's Shadow City | author = Mark Jacobson | work = [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] | date = May 2007 | accessdate = 30 April 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081121103109/http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/ | archive-date = 21 November 2008 | url-status = dead | author-link = The Lampshade: A Holocaust Detective Story from Buchenwald to New Orleans }}\n* [http://economist.com/world/asia/displaystory.cfm?story_id=10311293 \"Urban poverty in India: A flourishing slum\"] and [http://economist.com/world/asia/displaystory.cfm?story_id=10311257 \"Recycling: A soul-searching business\"], ''[[The Economist]]'', 19 December 2007\n* [http://www.livemint.com/dharavi.htm Everyone Wants a Slice of the Dharavi Pie \u2013 Live Mint]\n* [https://www.tabloidxo.com/dharavi-mumbai.jsp Facts About Asia's Largest Slum, Dharavi, Mumbai - TabloidXO]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dharavi.org dharavi.org: A participatory site on Dharavi]\n\n{{Mumbai topics}}\n{{Mumbai metropolitan area}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Slums of Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Squats in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the locality in Mumbai|other uses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = |settlement_type\n| image_skyline                   = File:Dharavi slum in Mumbai, India August 2009 4.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = Dharavi slum in 2009\n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Mumbai\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|19.040208|N|72.85085|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = Metro\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Mumbai]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 2.165\n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_density_km2          = 277,136.3 \u2013 461,893.8\n| population_est                  = 600,000 \u2013 1,000,000\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2016\n| literacy rate                   = 83.13 (as per 2001 census)\n| demographics_type1              = Language\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN CODE]]\n| postal_code                     = 400017\n| area_code                       = 022\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone Code\n| registration_plate              = MH-01\n| blank1_name_sec1                = Civic agency\n| blank1_info_sec1                = [[Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation|BMC]]\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n[[Image:Principaux Bidonvilles.png|225px|Dharavi compared to other large slums in the world. Map according to [[Mike Davis (scholar)|Mike Davis]].|thumb|right]]\n\n'''Dharavi''' is a [[locality (settlement)|locality]] in [[Mumbai]], Maharashtra, India, considered to be one of the world's largest [[Slum|slums]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Dharavi-in-Mumbai-is-no-longer-Asias-largest-slum/articleshow/9119450.cms|publisher=Times of India|access-date=9 November 2018|year=2011|title=Dharavi in Mumbai is no longer Asia's largest slum|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111002239/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Dharavi-in-Mumbai-is-no-longer-Asias-largest-slum/articleshow/9119450.cms|archive-date=11 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The next billion users : digital life beyond the West|last=Arora|first=Payal|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=2019|isbn=9780674983786|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=75|oclc=1057240289}}</ref> Dharavi has an area of just over {{convert|2.1|km2|sqmi acre}}<ref name=\"Shanty-towns emerge targets for development\">{{cite news |url=http://www.livemint.com/Money/1V0Zs8oNNvbAWEP6xHQQzN/Shantytowns-emerge-targets-for-development.html |title=Shanty-towns emerge targets for development |work=Livemint |access-date=27 December 2016 |date=6 July 2007 |author=Gayatri Ramanathan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119202545/http://www.livemint.com/Money/1V0Zs8oNNvbAWEP6xHQQzN/Shantytowns-emerge-targets-for-development.html |archive-date=19 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a population of about 700,000. With a [[population density]] of over {{pop density|600000|2.165|km2|sqmi|prec=0}}, Dharavi is one of the most densely populated areas in the world. \n\nThe Dharavi slum was founded in 1884 during the British colonial era, and grew in part because of an expulsion of factories and residents from the peninsular city centre by the colonial government, and from the migration of poor rural Indians into urban Mumbai. For this reason, Dharavi is currently a highly multi-religious, multi-ethnic, and diverse settlement.<ref name=\"Sharma, Kalpana 2000\">Sharma, Kalpana; \"Rediscovering Dharavi: Story From Asia's Largest Slum\" (2000) \u2013 Penguin Books {{ISBN|0-14-100023-6}}</ref>\n\nDharavi has an active informal economy in which numerous household enterprises employ many of the slum residents{{ndash}}<ref name=\"Ahmed\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7676337.stm | work=BBC News | title=Indian slum hit by New York woes | date=20 October 2008 | accessdate=1 May 2010 | first=Zubair | last=Ahmed | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023153647/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7676337.stm | archive-date=23 October 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> leather, textiles and pottery products are among the goods made inside Dharavi. The total annual turnover has been estimated at over {{USD}}1 billion.<ref name=\"nyenrode\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nyenrode.nl/businesstopics/europeindia/Pages/%E2%80%9CJaiHo%E2%80%9DDharavi.aspx |title=Jai Ho Dharavi |publisher=Nyenrode Business Universiteit |accessdate=5 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531175111/http://www.nyenrode.nl/businesstopics/europeindia/Pages/%E2%80%9CJaiHo%E2%80%9DDharavi.aspx |archive-date=31 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDharavi has suffered from many epidemics and other disasters, asincluding a widespread plague in 1896 which killed over half of the population of Mumbai.<ref name=\"Swaminathan, M. 1995\">Swaminathan, M. (1995). Aspects of urban poverty in Bombay. Environment and Urbanization, 7(1), 133\u2013144</ref> Though large sums of money have been borrowed by the Indian government in the guise of improving sanitation in Dharavi, none of these have materialized into any development on the ground.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Mumbai Slum Sanitation Program \u2013 Partnering with Slum Communities for SustainableSanitation in a Megalopolis |date=1 September 2006 |publisher=World bank |location=Washington |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/620841468041130033/pdf/384560IN0Mumbai0slum01PUBLIC1.pdf |accessdate=15 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815152603/http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/620841468041130033/pdf/384560IN0Mumbai0slum01PUBLIC1.pdf |archive-date=15 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\n<br />\n\n==Dharavi History==\nIn the 18th century, Dharavi was an island with a predominantly mangrove swamp.<ref name=\"origins\">{{cite book|last=D'Cunha|first=Jose Gerson|title=The Origins of Bombay|publisher=Asian Educational Services|location=Bombay|year=1900|edition=3|page=265|chapter=IV The Portuguese Period|isbn=978-81-206-0815-3|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=miD5YO05jpUC&dq=the+origins+of+bombay|access-date=4 January 2009}}</ref> It was a sparsely populated village before the late 19th century, inhabited by [[Koli people|Koli]] fishermen.<ref name=\"natgeo\">{{Cite news | url = http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/ | title = Dharavi Mumbai's Shadow City | author = Mark Jacobson | work = [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] | date = May 2007 | access-date = 30 April 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081121103109/http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/ | archive-date = 21 November 2008 | url-status = dead | author-link = The Lampshade: A Holocaust Detective Story from Buchenwald to New Orleans }}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = Globalization and Community, Volume 23 : Durable Slum : Dharavi and the Right to Stay Put in Globalizing Mumbai|last = Weinstein|first = Liza|publisher = University of Minnesota Press|date = June 2014|isbn = 9780816683109|location = Minneapolis, MN, USA|pages = 5}}</ref> Dharavi was then referred to as the village of [[Koliwada]].<ref name=jn2010/>\n\n===Colonial era===\nMumbai has been one of the centers of India's urbanization for 200 years. In the 1850s, after decades of urban growth under [[East India Company]] and [[British Raj]], the city's population reached half a million. The urban area then covered mostly the southern extension of Mumbai peninsula, the population density was over 10 times higher than London at that time.<ref name=jn2010>Jan Nijman, A STUDY OF SPACE IN MUMBAI'S SLUMS, Tijdschrift Voor economic en social geographies, Volume 101, Issue 1, pages 4\u201317, February 2010</ref>\n\n[[File:Shanty dwellings, Railway tracks and Mosque in Dharavi Slum Mumbai India February 2010.jpg|thumb|left|Shanty dwellings next to railway tracks in Dharavi (about 2010). A mosque inside the slum is visible. The railway network provides mass transit to the slum residents.]]\nThe most polluting industries were tanneries, and the first tannery moved from peninsular Mumbai into Dharavi in 1887. People who worked with leather, typically a profession of lowest Hindu castes and of Muslim Indians, moved into Dharavi. Other early settlers included the Kumbars, a large Gujarati community of potters (another polluting industry). The colonial government granted them a 99-year land-lease in 1895. Rural migrants looking for jobs poured into Mumbai, and its population soared past 1 million. Other artisans, like the [[embroidery]] workers from [[Uttar Pradesh]], started the ready-made garments trade.<ref name=\"NatGeo\"/> These industries created jobs, labor moved in, but there was no government effort to plan or invest in any infrastructure in or near Dharavi. The living quarters and small scale factories grew haphazardly, without provision for sanitation, drains, safe drinking water, roads or other basic services. But some ethnic, caste and religious communities that have settled in Dharavi at that time helped build the settlement of Dharavi, by forming organizations and political parties, building school and temples, constructing homes and factories.<ref name=\":0\" /> Dharavi's first mosque, Badi Masjid, started in 1887 and the oldest Hindu temple, Ganesh Mandir, was built in 1913.<ref name=jn2010/>\n\n===Post-independence===\nAt India's independence from colonial rule in 1947, Dharavi had grown to be the largest slum in Mumbai and all of India. It still had a few empty spaces, which continued to serve as waste-dumping grounds for operators across the city.<ref name=jn2010/> Mumbai, meanwhile, continued to grow as a city. Soon Dharavi was surrounded by the city, and became a key hub for informal economy.<ref>, Eyre, L. (1990), The shanty towns of central Bombay. Urban Geography 11, pages 130\u2013152</ref> Starting from the 1950s, proposals for Dharavi redevelopment plans periodically came out, but most of these plans failed because of lack of financial banking and/or political support.<ref name=\":0\" /> Dharavi's Co-operative Housing Society was formed in the 1960s to uplift the lives of thousands of slum dwellers by the initiative of Shri. M.V. Duraiswamy, a well-known social worker and congress leader of that region. The society promoted 338 flats and 97 shops and was named as Dr. Baliga Nagar. By the late 20th century, Dharavi occupied about {{convert|432|acre|ha|order=flip}}, with an astounding population density of more than 2900 people per hectare (1200/acre).<ref name=jn2010/><ref>Graber et al. (2005), Living and working in slums of Mumbai. Working paper 36. Magdeburg: Otto-von-Guericke Universitat, Netherlands</ref>\n\n=== Redevelopment plans ===\n[[Image:Pottery unit in Dharavi, Mumbai.jpg|thumb|left|A traditional pottery unit in Dharavi.]]\n\n[[File:Dharavi slum in Mumbai, India August 2009 3.jpg|thumb|left|Street vendors and farmers market along the road passing through Dharavi slum in Mumbai.]]\nThere have been many plans since 1997 to redevelop Dharavi like the former slums of Hong Kong such as [[Tai Hang]]. In 2004, the cost of redevelopment was estimated to be {{IRs|5000|c}}.<ref name=\"economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/Calls-to-scrap-Dharavi-makeover-gain-ground/articleshow/6363548.cms | work=The Times of India | title=Calls to scrap Dharavi makeover gain ground | date=20 August 2010 | access-date=3 November 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925015929/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/Calls-to-scrap-Dharavi-makeover-gain-ground/articleshow/6363548.cms | archive-date=25 September 2010 | url-status=live }}</ref> Companies from around the world have bid to redevelop Dharavi,<ref name=\"livemint.com\">{{cite web |author=Madhurima Nandy |url=http://www.livemint.com/2010/04/23222011/US-firm-exits-Dharavi-project.html?d=1 |title=US firm exits Dharavi project citing delays |publisher=Livemint |date=23 April 2010 |accessdate=7 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916195031/http://www.livemint.com/2010/04/23222011/US-firm-exits-Dharavi-project.html?d=1 |archive-date=16 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> including [[Lehman Brothers]], Dubai's Limitless and Singapore's Capitaland Ltd.<ref name=\"livemint.com\"/> In 2010, it was estimated to cost {{IRs|15000|c}} to redevelop.<ref name=\"economictimes.indiatimes.com\"/>\n\nThe latest urban [[redevelopment]] plan proposed for the Dharavi area is managed by American-trained architect Mukesh Mehta<ref name=\"NatGeo\"/> The plan involves the construction of {{convert|30000000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of [[houses|housing]], schools, parks and roads to serve the 57,000 families residing in the area, along with {{convert|40000000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of residential and commercial space for sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/UnouoCTZDd8YLPeRrethTP/Dharavi-redevelopment-plan-is-robbing-us-of-space-residents.html|title=Dharavi redevelopment plan is robbing us of space: residents|date=5 September 2007|publisher=Live Mint|accessdate=7 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210194254/http://www.livemint.com/Politics/UnouoCTZDd8YLPeRrethTP/Dharavi-redevelopment-plan-is-robbing-us-of-space-residents.html|archive-date=10 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> There is still a significant local opposition to the plans, largely because existing residents still feel {{convert|350|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of revised permanent alternate accommodation per tenant is not adequate each. Furthermore, only those families who lived in the area before 2000 are slated for resettlement. Concerns have also been raised by residents who fear that some of their small businesses in the \"informal\" sector may not be relocated under the redevelopment plan. Due to this opposition, a trust has been proposed called the Dharavi Community Land Trust that will be made up of community members, landowners, and neighborhood associations.\n\nIn 2008 German students Jens Kaercher and Lucas Schwind won a Next Generation prize for their innovative redevelopment strategy designed to protect the current residents from needing to relocate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lafargeholcim-foundation.org/projects/realizing-solutions-for-the-redevelopment-of-dharavi-mumbai-in|title=Realizing solutions for the redevelopment of Dharavi, Mumbai, In|last=info@lafargeholcim-foundation.org|first=LafargeHolcim Foundation for Sustainable Construction|website=LafargeHolcim Foundation website|access-date=20 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820235021/https://www.lafargeholcim-foundation.org/projects/realizing-solutions-for-the-redevelopment-of-dharavi-mumbai-in|archive-date=20 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOther redevelopment schemes include the \"Dharavi Masterplan\" devised by British architectural and engineering firm Foster + Partners, that proposes \"double-height spaces that create an intricate vertical landscape and reflect the community\u2019s way of life\" built-in phases that the firm says would \"eliminate the need for transit camps,\" instead catalyzing the rehabilitation of Dharavi \"from within.\"\n\nA Dubai based firm \u2013 SecLink group has planned to redevelop the slum into a completely new area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/dubai-firm-to-transform-asias-biggest-slum-1.62097740|title=Dubai firm to transform Asia's biggest slum|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=12 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412182103/https://gulfnews.com/business/dubai-firm-to-transform-asias-biggest-slum-1.62097740|archive-date=12 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On setting up of the SPV, the private firm will have to bring in the equity of Rs 400 crore, while the state government will invest another Rs 100 crore. The company planning to do it is also building infrastructure and affordable housing projects in Singapore and Dubai. Following the empowered committee\u2019s nod, the senior state officials said that an MoU will soon be executed between the state government, and the Dharavi Redevelopment Project Authority (DRPA) and the company. With an almost estimated cost of over Rs 26,000 crore, the Dharavi makeover project is the biggest brownfield redevelopment project in India. To make the redevelopment more economically viable, the state government\u2019s plan is involving transforming the region into a hub for commercial and business activity. Dharavi is close to the Bandra Kurla Complex, which is India\u2019s richest business district, and one of the richest in Asia.\n\n==Demographics==\nThe total current population of Dharavi slum is unknown, and estimates vary widely. Some sources suggest it is 300,000<ref name=claralewis>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-06/india/29742525_1_largest-slum-dharavi-nivara-hakk-sangharsh-samiti Dharavi in Mumbai is no longer Asia's largest slum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025211607/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-06/india/29742525_1_largest-slum-dharavi-nivara-hakk-sangharsh-samiti |date=25 October 2013 }} Clara Lewis, The Times of India (6 July 2011)</ref><ref name=\"Slums: The case of Mumbai, India\">[http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dpu-projects/Global_Report/pdfs/Mumbai.pdf Slums: The case of Mumbai, India] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403122230/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dpu-projects/Global_Report/pdfs/Mumbai.pdf |date=3 April 2018 }} Neelima Risbud, School of Planning and Architecture, New Delhi, India</ref> to about a million.<ref name=jimyardley>[http://www.deccanherald.com/content/216254/dharavi-self-created-special-economic.html Dharavi: Self-created special economic zone for the poor] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717231402/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/216254/dharavi-self-created-special-economic.html |date=17 July 2017 }} Jim Yardley, Deccan Herald (2010)</ref> With Dharavi spread over {{convert|500|acre|ha|order=flip}}, it is also estimated to have a population density of an incredible 869,565 people per square mile. With a literacy rate of 69%, Dharavi is the most literate slum in India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_mumbai-s-slums-are-india-s-most-literate_1015111 |title=Mumbai's slums are India's most literate \u2013 Mumbai \u2013 DNA |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date=27 February 2006 |accessdate=16 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728070119/http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_mumbai-s-slums-are-india-s-most-literate_1015111 |archive-date=28 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAbout 30% of the population of Dharavi is Muslim, compared to 13% average population of Muslims in India.<ref>[http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2007/05/dharavi-mumbai-slum/jonas-bendiksen-photography Dharavi: Mumbai's Shadow City] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214214727/http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2007/05/dharavi-mumbai-slum/jonas-bendiksen-photography |date=14 February 2018 }} National Geographic (2007)</ref><ref>[http://censusindia.gov.in/Census_And_You/religion.aspx Census Data: India] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315004939/http://censusindia.gov.in/Census_And_You/religion.aspx |date=15 March 2018 }} Government of India</ref> The Christian population is estimated to be about 6%,<ref>[http://nazrene.org/dharavi_deanery.html History of Dharavi churches] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127042243/http://nazrene.org/dharavi_deanery.html |date=27 November 2013 }} Dharavi Deanery (2011)</ref> while the rest are predominantly Hindus (63%), with some Buddhists and other minority religions. Among the Hindus, about 20% work on animal skin production, tanneries and leather goods. Other Hindus specialise in pottery work, textile goods manufacturing, retail and trade, distilleries and other caste professions \u2013 all of these as small-scale household operations. The slum residents are from all over India, people who migrated from rural regions of many different states.<ref>Sharma, Kalpana (2000). Rediscovering Dharavi: Stories from Asia's largest slum. Penguin Books India; {{ISBN|978-0141000237}}</ref> The slum has numerous mosques, temples and churches to serve people of Islam, Hindu and Christian faiths; with Badi Masjid, a mosque, as the oldest religious structure in Dharavi.\n\n==Location and characteristics==\n[[File:Bombaywardsmap''H-E''.PNG|thumb|220px|Dharavi is located in Ward H East, marked in dark blue, one of the many [[Administrative divisions of Mumbai|British-era administrative wards]] of Mumbai city limits (yellow). Dharavi is southern end of Ward H East, and other residential and commercial areas in the Ward marked in dark blue include [[Santacruz, Mumbai|Santacruz]], [[Vile Parle]] and [[Mahim]].]]\nDharavi is a large area situated between Mumbai's two main suburban railway lines, the Western and Central Railways. To the west of Dharavi are [[Mahim]] and [[Bandra]], and to the north lies the [[Mithi River]]. The Mithi River empties into the [[Arabian Sea]] through the [[Mahim Creek]]. The area of [[Antop Hill]] lies to the east while the locality called [[Matunga]] is located in the South. Due to its location and poor sewage and drainage systems, Dharavi particularly becomes vulnerable to floods during the [[wet season]].\n\nDharavi is considered one of the largest slums in the world. The low-rise building style and narrow street structure of the area make Dharavi very cramped and confined. Like most slums, it is overpopulated. Compared to Mumbai's urban [[floor space index]] (FSI) of a range from 5 to 15, in Dharavi it is about 13.3 [[citation needed]]. Government officials are considering changing the Dharavi's floor space index to 4. Despite the expensive Mumbai lifestyle, Dharavi provides a cheap alternative where rent is as low as Rs.1000 per month.\n\n==Economy==\n[[Image:An embroidery unit in Dharavi, Mumbai.jpg|thumb|left|An embroidery unit in Dharavi.]]\nIn addition to the traditional [[pottery]] and textile industries in Dharavi,<ref name=\"natgeo\"/> there is an increasingly large [[recycling]] industry, processing recyclable waste from other parts of [[Mumbai]]. Recycling in Dharavi is reported to employ approximately 250,000 people.<ref name=\"gua\" /> While recycling is a major industry in the neighborhood, it is also reported to be a source of heavy pollution in the area.<ref name=\"gua\" /> The district has an estimated 5000 businesses<ref>{{cite web |author=Madhurima Nandy |url=http://www.livemint.com/2010/03/23000503/Harvard-students-get-lessons-o.html?d=1 |title=Harvard students get lessons on Dharavi |publisher=Livemint |date=23 March 2010 |accessdate=7 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918192410/http://www.livemint.com/2010/03/23000503/Harvard-students-get-lessons-o.html?d=1 |archive-date=18 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and 15,000 single-room factories.<ref name=\"gua\">[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/world/story/0,,2026024,00.html Waste not, want not in the \u00a3700m slum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080106102248/http://observer.guardian.co.uk/world/story/0,,2026024,00.html |date=6 January 2008 }}, ''The Guardian'', 4 March 2007</ref> Two major suburban railways feed into Dharavi, making it an important commuting station for people in the area going to and from work.\n\nDharavi exports goods around the world.<ref name=\"Ahmed\"/> Often these consist of various leather products, jewellery, various accessories, and textiles. Markets for Dharavi's goods include stores in the United States, Europe, and the Middle East.<ref name=\"Ahmed\" /> The total (and largely informal economy) turnover is estimated to be between {{USD}}500 million,<ref name=\"nyenrode\"/> over {{USD}}650 million per year,<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/world/06/dharavi_slum/html/dharavi_slum_intro.stm|title = Dharavi|publisher = BBC|accessdate = 2 January 2010|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100906022807/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/world/06/dharavi_slum/html/dharavi_slum_intro.stm|archive-date = 6 September 2010|url-status = live}}</ref> to over {{USD}}1 billion per year.<ref name=\"gua\"/> The per capita income of the residents, depending on estimated population range of 300,000 to about 1 million, ranges between US$500 to US$2000 per year.\n\nA few travel operators offer guided tours through Dharavi, showing the industrial and the residential part of Dharavi and explaining about the problems and challenges Dharavi is facing. These tours give a deeper insight into a slum in general and Dharavi in particular.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/travel/destinations/india/article7124205.ece|title=Mumbai slum tour: why you should see Dharavi|accessdate=7 November 2012|publisher=Timesonline.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522184950/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/travel/destinations/india/article7124205.ece|archive-date=22 May 2010|url-status=live}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n== Utility services ==\nPotable water is supplied by the [[Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation|MCGM]] to Dharavi and the whole of Mumbai. However, a large amount of water is lost due to water thefts, illegal connection and leakage.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Now, a toll-free helpline to check water leakage, theft \u2013 Indian Express|url = http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/now-a-tollfree-helpline-to-check-water-lea/531630/|website = archive.indianexpress.com|publisher = |accessdate = 8 December 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150904001826/http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/now-a-tollfree-helpline-to-check-water-lea/531630/|archive-date = 4 September 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> The community also has a number of water wells that are sources of non-potable water.\n\n\nCooking gas is supplied in the form of [[Liquefied petroleum gas|liquefied petroleum gas cylinders]] sold by state-owned oil companies,<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-cooking-gas-cylinders-to-be-sold-at-petrol-pumps-1865090|title = Cooking gas cylinders to be sold at petrol pumps|date = 24 July 2013|work = Daily News and Analysis.|access-date = 8 December 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150615204630/http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-cooking-gas-cylinders-to-be-sold-at-petrol-pumps-1865090|archive-date = 15 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> as well as through [[Natural gas|piped natural gas]] supplied by Mahanagar Gas Limited.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-piped-gas-becomes-more-attractive-for-the-kitchen-1740662|title = Piped gas becomes more attractive for the kitchen|date = 14 September 2012|work = Daily News and Analysis|access-date = |via = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150615203513/http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-piped-gas-becomes-more-attractive-for-the-kitchen-1740662|archive-date = 15 June 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThere are settlement houses that still do not have legal connections to the utility service and thus rely on illegal connection to the water and power supply which means a water and power shortage for the residents in Dharavi.\n\n===Sanitation issues===\n[[Image:Dharavi Slum in Mumbai.jpg|thumb|Inside Dharavi]]\n[[File:Mumbai 03-2016 49 Dharavi near Mahim Junction.jpg|thumb|Mosque in Dharavi]]\nDharavi has severe problems with public health. Water access derives from public standpipes stationed throughout the slum. Additionally, with the limited lavatories they have, they are extremely filthy and broken down to the point of being unsafe. Mahim Creek is a local river that is widely used by local residents for urination and defecation causing the spread of contagious diseases.<ref name=\"natgeo\"/> The open sewers in the city drain to the creek causing a spike in water pollutants, septic conditions, and foul odors. Due to the air pollutants, diseases such as lung cancer, tuberculosis, and asthma are common among residents. There are government proposals in regards to improving Dharavi's sanitation issues. The residents have a section where they wash their clothes in water that people defecate in. This spreads the amount of disease as doctors have to deal with over 4,000 cases of typhoid a day. There is also an average of 1 toilet per 500 people.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Epidemics and other disasters==\nDharavi has experienced a long history of epidemics and natural disasters, sometimes with significant loss of lives. The first plague to devastate Dharavi, along with other settlements of Mumbai happened in 1896, when nearly half of the population died. A series of plagues and other epidemics continued to affect Dharavi, and Mumbai in general, for the next 25 years, with high rates of mortality.<ref>Gandy, M. (2008), Landscapes of disaster: water, modernity, and urban fragmentation in Mumbai. Environment and planning. A, 40(1), 108</ref><ref>Renapurkar, D. M. (1988). Distribution and Susceptibility of Xenopsylla astia to DDT in Maharashtra State, India. International Journal of Tropical Insect Science, 9(03), 377\u2013380</ref> [[Dysentery]] epidemics have been common throughout the years and explained by the high population density of Dharavi. Other reported epidemics include [[Typhoid fever|typhoid]], [[cholera]], [[leprosy]], [[amoebiasis]] and [[polio]].<ref name=\"Swaminathan, M. 1995\"/><ref>[http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/09/12/india-restarts-battle-against-leprosy/?_r=0 India Restarts Battle Against Leprosy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323021706/http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/09/12/india-restarts-battle-against-leprosy/?_r=0 |date=23 March 2014 }} Anjali Thomas, New York Times (12 September 2013)</ref> For example, in 1986, a cholera epidemic was reported, where most patients were children of Dharavi. Typical patients to arrive in hospitals were in late and critical care condition, and the mortality rates were abnormally high.<ref>Mehta et al., An outbreak of cholera in children of Bombay slums, Journal of Diarrhoeal Diseases Research, June 4(2): page 94</ref> In recent years, cases of drug resistant [[tuberculosis]] have been reported in Dharavi.<ref>Udwadia, Z. F., Pinto, L. M., & Uplekar, M. W. (2010). Tuberculosis management by private practitioners in Mumbai, India: has anything changed in two decades?. PLoS One, 5(8), e12023</ref><ref>Loewenberg, S. (2012), India reports cases of totally drug-resistant tuberculosis, The Lancet, 379(9812), 205</ref>\n\nFires and other disasters are common. For example, in January 2013, a fire destroyed many slum properties and caused injuries.<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dharavi-turns-into-fireball-as-flames-engulf-slum/1063044/ Dharavi turns into fireball as flames engulf slum] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125011615/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/dharavi-turns-into-fireball-as-flames-engulf-slum/1063044 |date=25 January 2013 }} Indian Express (22 January 2013)</ref> In 2005, massive floods caused deaths and extensive property damage.<ref>Samaddar, S., Misra, B. A., Chatterjee, R., & Tatano, H. (2012). [http://idrim.ir/index.php/idrim/article/viewFile/38/pdf_11 Understanding Community\u2019s Evacuation Intention Development Process in a Flood Prone Micro-hotspot]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Mumbai. IDRiM Journal, 2(2)</ref>\n\nThe [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]] also affected the slum. The first case was reported in April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Joshi |first1=Sahil |title=First coronavirus case reported from Mumbai's Dharavi slum |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/first-coronavirus-positive-case-reported-from-dharavi-in-mumbai-1662265-2020-04-01 |website=India Today |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==In the media==\n{{Quote\n |quote    = From the main road leading through Dharavi, the place makes a desperate impression. However, once having entered the narrow lanes Dharavi proves that the prejudice of slums as dirty, underdeveloped, and criminal places does not fit real living conditions. Sure, communal sanitation blocks that are mostly in a miserable condition and overcrowded space do not comfort the living. Inside the huts, it is, however, very clean, and some huts share some elements of beauty. Nice curtains at the windows and balconies covered by flowers and plants indicate that people try to arrange their homes as cosy and comfortable as possible.\n |source   = Denis Gruber et al. (2005)<ref>Denis Gruber, Andrea Kirschner, Sandra Mill, Manuela Schach, Steffen Schmekel, and Hardo Seligman, Living and Working in Slums of Mumbai, Otto-von-Guericke-Universit\u00e4t Magdeburg, Institut f\u00fcr Soziologie, Magdeburg, Germany, {{ISSN|1615-8229}} (April 2005)</ref>\n |width    = 125%\n |fontsize = 100%\n |bgcolor  = #CEECC2\n |align    = center\n}}\nDharavi was most notably used as the backdrop in the film ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' (2008).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mendes|first=Ana Cristina|date=2010|title=Showcasing India Unshining: Film Tourism in Danny Boyle'sSlumdog Millionaire|journal=Third Text|language=en|volume=24|issue=4|pages=471\u2013479|doi=10.1080/09528822.2010.491379|issn=0952-8822}}</ref> It has also been depicted in a number of Indian films, including ''[[Deewaar]]'' (1975), ''[[Nayakan]]'' (1987), ''[[Salaam Bombay!]]'' (1988), ''[[Parinda]]'' (1989), ''[[Dharavi (film)|Dharavi]]'' (1991), ''[[Bombay (film)|Bombay]]'' (1995), [[Ram Gopal Varma]]'s \"[[Ram Gopal Varma#Indian gangster trilogy|Indian Gangster Trilogy]]\" (1998\u20132005), the ''[[Sarkar (2005 film)|Sarkar]]'' series (2005\u20132008), ''[[Footpath (2003 film)|Footpath]]'' (2003), ''[[Black Friday (2004 film)|Black Friday]]'' (2004), ''[[No Smoking (2007 film)|No Smoking]]'' (2007), ''[[Traffic Signal (film)|Traffic Signal]]'' (2007), ''[[Aamir (film)|Aamir]]'' (2008), ''[[Mankatha]]'' (2011), ''[[Thuppakki]]'' (2012), ''[[Thalaivaa]]'' (2013), ''[[Bhoothnath Returns]]'' (2014), ''[[Kaala (2018 film)|Kaala]]'' (2018) and ''[[Gully Boy]]'' (2019).\n\n''Dharavi, Slum for Sale'' (2009) by Lutz Konermann and Rob Appleby is a German [[Documentary film|documentary]].<ref>{{IMDb title|1188984|Dharavi, Slum for Sale}}</ref> In a programme aired in the United Kingdom in January 2010, [[Kevin McCloud]] and Channel 4 aired a two-part series titled ''Slumming It''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/4homes/on-tv/kevin-mccloud-slumming-it/kevin-mccloud-slumming-it-episode-two-10-01-06_p_1.html |title=Slumming It: Dharavi |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=8 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118083854/http://www.channel4.com/4homes/on-tv/kevin-mccloud-slumming-it/kevin-mccloud-slumming-it-episode-two-10-01-06_p_1.html |archive-date=18 January 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> which centered around Dharavi and its inhabitants. The poem \"[[Blessing (poem)|Blessing]]\" by [[Imtiaz Dharker]] is about Dharavi not having enough water. ''[[For The Win]]'', by [[Cory Doctorow]], is partially set in Dharavi. In 2014, Belgian researcher Katrien Vankrunkelsven made a 22-minute film on Dharavi which is entitled ''The Way of Dharavi''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s_0X0wIvqVM|title=Documentary \u2013 The Way Of Dharavi 2014|last=Sse Productions bvba|date=3 April 2015|publisher=|access-date=30 April 2017|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017233205/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s_0X0wIvqVM|archive-date=17 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Poverty in India]]\n* [[List of slums in India]]\n* [[Urbanisation in India]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n*Dharavi: Documenting Informalities. Practical Action June 2018. Jonatan Habib Engqvist and Maria Lantz. {{ISBN|978-1853397103}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{commons category}}\n* Sharma, Kalpana; \"Rediscovering Dharavi: Story From Asia's Largest Slum\" (2000) \u2013 Penguin Books {{ISBN|0-14-100023-6}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/spl/hi/world/06/dharavi_slum/html/dharavi_slum_intro.stm \"Life in a Slum\" \u2013 BBC News]\n* {{Cite news | url = http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/ | title = Dharavi Mumbai's Shadow City | author = Mark Jacobson | work = [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] | date = May 2007 | accessdate = 30 April 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081121103109/http://www7.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0705/feature3/ | archive-date = 21 November 2008 | url-status = dead | author-link = The Lampshade: A Holocaust Detective Story from Buchenwald to New Orleans }}\n* [http://economist.com/world/asia/displaystory.cfm?story_id=10311293 \"Urban poverty in India: A flourishing slum\"] and [http://economist.com/world/asia/displaystory.cfm?story_id=10311257 \"Recycling: A soul-searching business\"], ''[[The Economist]]'', 19 December 2007\n* [http://www.livemint.com/dharavi.htm Everyone Wants a Slice of the Dharavi Pie \u2013 Live Mint]\n* [https://www.tabloidxo.com/dharavi-mumbai.jsp Facts About Asia's Largest Slum, Dharavi, Mumbai - TabloidXO]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dharavi.org dharavi.org: A participatory site on Dharavi]\n\n{{Mumbai topics}}\n{{Mumbai metropolitan area}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Slums of Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Squats in India]]\n", "